# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apartment
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The two buildings occupy rectangular footprints, being arranged on a 3-by-5 grid of square bays, each measuring 21 feet (6.4 m) on each side.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The south tower at 860 North Lake Shore Drive is oriented west–east, while the north tower at 880 North Lake Shore Drive is oriented north–south.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] There is an arcade at the ground (first) story of both buildings, as well as glass walls around each building's lobbies.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] On and above the second story of both buildings, the windows are separated vertically by mullion bars with I-beams, and they are divided horizontally by spandrel panels.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Each bay has four window panes per story, while different bays are separated vertically by steel plates.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Both buildings have a steel superstructure encased in concrete, as well as a structural core for elevators, stairs, hallways, bathrooms, and kitchens.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The basement has a garage, and each building's ground story has a lobby.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] On the upper floors, there were originally a combined 116 six-bedroom apartments and 152 three-and-a-half-room apartments.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Many original design elements remain intact, though the apartments have been rearranged over the years.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The real estate developer Herbert Greenwald became acquainted with Mies in 1946, hiring the architect to design the Promontory Apartments on Lake Shore Drive.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The design of 860–880 Lake Shore Drive is derived from an alternative design for the Promontory Apartments with a glass-and-steel facade.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Greenwald and Robert Hall McCormick announced in April 1949 that they would build two 25-story cooperative apartment towers at 860–880 Lake Shore Drive.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] A formal groundbreaking ceremony took place on December 17, 1949, and almost all the apartments had been sold by mid-1951.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Residents moved in even before the buildings were formally completed in August 1952.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The lobbies and their plaza were restored starting in 2008.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Despite initial controversy over their unconventional style, which was shared by few buildings in the United States, the 860–880 Lake Shore Drive towers were highly regarded after they were completed.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] After the towers were finished, many glass-box skyscrapers were built worldwide.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The buildings are located at 860 and 880 North Lake Shore Drive, in the Streeterville neighborhood of the Near North Side of Chicago, Illinois, United States.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The complex spans 1.17 acres (0.47 hectares), and has a frontage of 103 feet (31 m) on Delaware Place to the north, 242 feet (74 m) on Lake Shore Drive to the east, and 206 feet (63 m) on Chestnut Street to the south.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] It faces Lake Michigan immediately to the east.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] While Delaware Place and Chestnut Street are aligned with Chicago's street grid, Lake Shore Drive runs at a slight angle from northwest to southeast, following the shoreline of Lake Michigan.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The buildings are slightly north of the Chicago Loop and east of Michigan Avenue.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The apartment towers at 900–910 North Lake Shore are immediately to the north.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Prior to the buildings' completion, the site had been occupied by a mansion belonging to Edith Rockefeller McCormick.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] By 1949 (just before the site was developed), the McCormick family's McCormick Management Corporation owned the northern half of the site, while Northwestern University had obtained the southern half in 1944 from Robert R.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The towers at 860–880 Lake Shore Drive were designed by the modernist architect Ludwig Mies van der Rohe for the developer Herbert Greenwald.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Holsman, Holsman, Klekamp & Taylor were the consulting architects, and Pace Associates were the associated architects.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Kornacher was the engineer, and Richard Kelly the lighting designer.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Both towers are 26 stories high, with a height of 270 feet (82 m), and are designed in the International Style.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] They are the first high-rise buildings Mies designed.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] 860–880 Lake Shore Drive were part of a trend of glassy skyscrapers in major American cities, other examples of which included the United Nations Secretariat Building in New York City.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The writer Franz Schulze described earlier International-style designs, such as the PSFS Building in Philadelphia and 330 West 42nd Street in New York, as "precedents" to the Lake Shore Drive towers' design.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] 860–880 Lake Shore Drive's relatively simple designs contrast significantly with Mies's earlier designs such as the German Pavilion in Barcelona or the Villa Tugendhat in Brno, which used materials like travertine and marble.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Mies, who had a reputation as a minimalist architect, adhered to the principle "less is more", as demonstrated in his self-proclaimed "skin and bones" designs.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] In designing the buildings, he purposely disregarded the effects of sunlight exposure and wind gusts.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The towers' identical appearance, vertical mullions, and the use of a steel frame for articulation set them apart from other buildings of the time, even though none of the actual superstructures are visible on the buildings' facades.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The two buildings have rectangular footprints and are arranged on perpendicular axes to each other.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Their superstructures are constructed on a grid of square bays measuring 21 feet (6.4 m) on each side.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The longer sides of each building are five bays wide, while the shorter sides are three bays wide.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Unlike older apartment buildings on Lake Shore Drive, which tended to be perpendicular to that street, 860–880 Lake Shore Drive was built perpendicularly to the side streets and the Chicago street grid.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] 860 North Lake Shore Drive (the south tower) occupies the southeastern corner of the site, with its shorter sides oriented eastward and westward, while 880 North Lake Shore Drive (the north tower) is at the northeastern corner, with its shorter sides oriented northward and southward.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The offset positioning maximizes the number of apartments that oversee the lake.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Blair Kamin of the *Chicago Tribune* wrote that, from above, the positioning of the towers made it seem like they were "sliding past each other".
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] An arcade surrounds the ground (or first) story of both buildings, exposing some of the superstructure's columns to plain view.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The ground stories of both buildings have glass walls; the lobbies have transparent glass and the service areas next to each lobby opaque glass, similar to Mies's earlier German Pavilion.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The glass walls are backlit from inside during the nighttime, giving the impression that each tower was floating.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Although Mies's decision to use opaque windows has been cited as a practical way to conceal the mechanical equipment, they also highlighted the superstructure's columns at night.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The soffits at the buildings' perimeters, along the ceilings of each arcade, have powerful spotlights that illuminate the arcades' floors and provide additional lighting for the lobbies' glass facades.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Specially made lenses are placed over the lamps to distribute the light evenly over the facades.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The lobbies have travertine floors and are connected by a travertine walkway.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The pathway connects two travertine plazas surrounding the towers, creating a plinth.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Around 1,100 stone slabs weighing up to 175 pounds (79 kg) each were used to construct the lobbies, walkway, and the plazas outside the buildings.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Just above ground level, a steel canopy runs above a walkway connecting the south tower's northern facade and the north tower's southern facade.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] On and above the second story of both buildings, the facade's glass windows run from the floor to the ceiling.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The windows are separated vertically by mullion bars and horizontally by spandrel panels between different floors; the aluminum mullions run nearly the buildings' entire height.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] On each floor, each bay has a 21-by-9-foot (6.4 m × 2.7 m) opening.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] There are four window panes per opening, which are set into aluminum frames.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The panes are divided into a larger upper section and a smaller lower section, which swing inward from hinges on the ceiling and floor, respectively.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The buildings have a combined 3,232 panes with 130,000 square feet (12,000 m2) of glass.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] To prevent rain from entering the buildings during high winds, steel and rubber strips are affixed to the windows' edges.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The windows' dimensions and the protruding mullions allowed Mies to emphasize both buildings' vertical design details over their horizontal details.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The centers of each mullion are spaced 5+1⁄4 feet (1.6 m) apart, corresponding to one-fourth the width of the bays inside.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Protruding I-beams are welded to the mullions.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Each of the I-beams is about 8 inches (20 cm) thick, and the tops and bottoms of the I-beams are cut off, allowing the beams' cross sections to be seen.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Architectural writers criticized the I-beams when the buildings were constructed, since the material was being used for purely decorative purposes, and since the use of decorative design details ostensibly contravened Mies's longstanding tendency not to use materials unless absolutely necessary.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Mies told one reporter that there was both a "real reason" and a "good reason" for the I-beams' existence.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] While the "good reason" was to stiffen steel plates in the superstructure, the "real reason" was that the I-beams were intended to represent the steel superstructure, which was exposed only at the ground level.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The I-beams also broke up the otherwise-flat facades, and, as sunlight hit the I-beams throughout the day, they cast shadows in specific patterns.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] All exterior steel was coated in black enamel paint, without any other surface finish.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The designs of 860–880 Lake Shore Drive's superstructures and facades are closely correlated, in contrast to Mies's later designs where the facade had little, if anything, to do with the superstructure.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Each bay is divided by concrete-encased columns at the buildings' perimeters.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The concrete columns cannot be seen from the outside, as they are hidden behind steel plates, which have I-beams welded to them, matching the designs of the mullions between the windows.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] In both buildings, the columns at each corner are covered with steel plates on two sides.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Although the mullions are equidistant, the columns protrude about 9 inches (23 cm) into each bay, so the two outer windows in each bay (immediately next to the columns) are narrower than the two inner windows.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Adjacent mullions and spandrels for rectangles that were similar in proportion to the footprints of each building.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] 860–880 Lake Shore Drive is Mies's only design where the curtain wall is flush with the exterior columns; in all of his other designs, the curtain wall is either hung outside or was recessed into the superstructure.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The facades lack other traditional design details such as cornices, and there are also no balconies.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] When the towers were built, exposed steel superstructures above a building's first story were banned under Chicago's building codes, preventing Mies from exposing the buildings' steel frames on the upper floors.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] As a result, the columns in both buildings' superstructures (including at the perimeter) are encased in concrete above the ground story, which influenced his decision to put I-beams on the facade.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Vierendeel trusses are used to support the upper floors; although the trusses are light, they also tend to make the upper stories sway considerably.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The superstructures are made primarily of steel, as opposed to Mies's later 900–910 North Lake Shore Drive, where the frames are made entirely of concrete.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Beneath both buildings are two basements with storage space, deep freezers, laundry rooms, and sitting rooms.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] There is also a garage below both buildings; sources disagree on whether it has 100 or 116 parking spots.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Barcelona chairs are installed in the lobby of either tower.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The core of each building is used for circulation and includes elevators, hallways, and stairs.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Each building has two elevators that serve all stories.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The cores also contain each apartment's bathrooms and kitchens.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Each of the upper stories measures 10 feet (3.0 m) high, with either three and a half or six rooms in each apartment.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The original plans called for 92 large units and 192 small units, but 40 of the small units were combined to make 20 large units, for a total of 116 large apartments and 152 small apartments.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] All of the south tower's apartments and half of the north tower's apartments had windows on two sides.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The six-room units were originally located in the south tower, while the three-and-a-half-room units were in the north tower.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The larger apartments had three bedrooms each, spanning 1,400 square feet (130 m2), and the smaller units had one bedroom each, spanning 700 square feet (65 m2).
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] There were initially four apartments per floor in the south tower and eight per floor in the north tower.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The apartment layouts are influenced by the facades' designs and the buildings' footprints.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Mies had originally proposed arranging the apartments in an open plan, but Greenwald forced Mies to add walls between the rooms in each apartment.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] After his open-plan floor layouts were rejected, Mies almost quit the project entirely.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Mies also wanted to add a service entrance to each apartment, but this was discarded from the final plan.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The final arrangement was a compromise between Mies's original concept and Greenwald's requirements, and many of the units have since been combined.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Similarly to Mies's earlier Farnsworth House in Plano, Illinois, bedrooms and other living spaces are positioned around the kitchens and bathrooms in the core.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The dining alcoves in the north tower's apartments abut the core, while the alcoves in the south tower's apartments abut the curtain wall.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The building's 21-by-21-foot (6.4 by 6.4 m) square bays influenced the interior layout; for example, living rooms span the entire width of a bay, while dining rooms and bedrooms span half a bay.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] When the buildings were finished in 1951, the apartments had a myriad of closets, and Mies said that the full-height windows on the facade provided a plethora of natural light.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The units also have radiant heating systems, and there are convection heaters near the windows.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Originally, the towers had no building-wide air conditioning; Mies's original plans for a central air system, which would have cooled the apartments, were canceled due to its expense.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Instead, dozens of residents retrofitted their apartments with air-conditioning units.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Mies wanted each floor to look exactly the same from the outside, so the same gray color was used for all of the curtains directly behind each window.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Behind each curtain is a rail where occupants could install a curtain of their own design.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Several tenants decorated their own apartments in their own styles.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Though the finishes, kitchens, and bedrooms in some apartments have since been modified, much of Mies's original design remains intact.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] In 1946, Greenwald became acquainted with Mies, who then was developing Farnsworth House.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Though Greenwald was thirty years younger than Mies, they remained frequent collaborators until Greenwald died in 1959.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Greenwald was motivated to develop buildings of high architectural quality.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Additionally, the 1933 Century of Progress world's fair had spurred the construction of modern architecture in Chicago, and architects such as Mies and Loebl Schlossman & Hackl had been inspired to build modernist structures there.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The first building Greenwald hired Mies to design was the Promontory Apartments on South Lake Shore Drive, completed in 1949.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Due to World War II-era steel shortages, that building had a reinforced concrete facade, rather than the steel-and-glass facade Mies had wanted.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Mies nonetheless drew up an alternate plan for a structure with a steel-and-glass facade, which he later reused for 860–880 Lake Shore Drive.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Before the Lake Shore Drive project, Mies had been considering a steel-and-glass skyscraper for three decades but had been unable to realize his design; as early as 1920, he had been drawing up designs for towers with steel skeletons.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] After the Promontory Apartments were completed, Mies and Greenwald had considered several other designs along Lake Michigan, which were ultimately not built.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] After the Promontory Apartments, Mies's next collaboration with Greenwald was at 860–880 Lake Shore Drive.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Northwestern University, the seller of the land, still owned a parcel to the west.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] When the site of 860–880 Lake Shore Drive was acquired in 1948, Northwestern had agreed to sell only if Lake Michigan remained visible from the other plot to the west.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] This requirement prompted Greenwald and his development partner—Robert Hall McCormick, the son of Robert R.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] McCormick—to plan two buildings on the site, rather than one.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Greenwald and McCormick announced plans for two 25-story cooperative apartment towers at 860–880 Lake Shore Drive in April 1949.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] There would be 92 six-room apartments, 192 three-and-a-half-room apartments, and 25 studio apartments, along with 100 parking spaces.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The development would have a steel-and-glass facade, since the wartime steel shortage was no longer as severe.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The idea for a glass facade was attributed to McCormick.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The buildings were to be financed with a $3.1 million mortgage loan, which would be paid off over twenty years and split between the tenants.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Since the buildings were to be co-ops, each tenant also had to pay a monthly maintenance fee.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The real-estate company Baird & Warner, acting on behalf of the developers, tried to obtain financing, but prospective lenders were reluctant to give money to a development with so many novel design features.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] In July 1949, the Mutual Benefit Life Insurance Company agreed to lend $3.1 million.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Mies's employee Joseph Fujikawa worked with Holsman, Holsman, Klekamp & Taylor to create blueprints for the towers, and Charles B.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Genther of Pace Associates spent three months creating working drawings and soliciting bids from prospective construction contractors.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Unlike other apartment buildings, where design started with the facade and worked inward, Mies designed the superstructure first and the facade afterward.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The height of each tower was dictated by the need to maximize usable space on the upper stories, given the limited floor area available.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The architectural historian William Jordy later recalled that Mies had considered even a 12-story building to be too tall and that Mies thought the towers "became very thin" at their final height, considering the buildings' increasing height-to-width ratios.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] A formal groundbreaking ceremony took place on December 17, 1949, at which point more than half of the apartments had been sold.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The American Bridge Company received the contract for the buildings' steelwork, while Greenwald's company Metropolitan Structures Inc. was the general contractor.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] To provide seating for the lobbies, Mies asked one of his acolytes to consult photographs of Barcelona chairs (which Mies had designed for the Barcelona Pavilion two decades prior) and draw up modern plans.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Work on the south tower was delayed after workers discovered a derelict water tunnel 83 feet (25 m) below the ground, which had served the Near North Side of Chicago until around 1890.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Five of the south tower's footings had to be relocated as a result.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Although the north tower's superstructure had reached the 14th story by July 1950, the south tower's foundation was still being constructed.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] By then, 72% of the units had been sold for between $13,500 and $27,000 each.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The facade was constructed modularly, with two-story-high panels manufactured elsewhere and then welded together.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The panels divided the facade into bays with four windows per story.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] In contrast to earlier concrete buildings, where wet concrete was poured into temporary wooden formwork, the concrete columns at both buildings were poured into a formwork made of steel plates.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The steel plates remained on the facades after the columns were poured, eliminating the need to cover up the concrete with some other material.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Mies contemplated painting the steel beams red, yellow, or some other color, but he ultimately decided to paint them black.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The windows were also assembled from inside the building, eliminating the need to use scaffolding on the facade.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] They were originally dubbed the "glass houses"; due to the materials used in the buildings, one source referred to them as the "World's First Multiple Glass House".
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] During construction, in 1951, a worker died after falling down an elevator shaft.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] In part because of Chicago's postwar housing shortage, the developers had sold 95% of the apartments in the buildings by June 1951.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] All of the six-room apartments had been sold by August, while only 17 three-and-a-half-room apartments remained.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Residents rapidly moved in while apartments were being completed.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The structures ultimately cost $6 million.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Averaging $10.38 per square foot ($111.7/m2), the buildings were less expensive than comparable apartment buildings of similar size, and they cost less than even the public housing complexes developed by the Chicago Housing Authority.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The buildings were formally completed in August 1952, and Mutual Benefit Life extended its $3.1 million mortgage on the buildings that year.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Robert Picking, a local architect, was the first resident to formally move in.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Although both pets and children were allowed to live in the buildings, the *Chicago Tribune* wrote that there were only 14 pets, fewer than a dozen teenagers, and two infants when the buildings were completed.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Apartment owners were allowed to rent out their units, but only for up to 24 months at a time.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Many residents moved to 860–880 Lake Shore Drive because of the shorefront location and because of the views out the full-height windows.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Mies owned an apartment on the 21st floor but did not live there, though he did bring students there for occasional tours.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The *Chicago Tribune* wrote that there was speculation that he did not want to hear his tenants' complaints, while the architect Bruce Graham said Mies had told him that there was nowhere to put the furniture.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The buildings' initial lack of air conditioning and their exposure to large amounts of direct sunlight, particularly during the summer, caused them to heat up.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] There were also no garbage chutes, and Mies was aware of leaks in the buildings even before their completion, having futilely tried to patch them.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Many tenants decided to install a second curtain behind the buildings' original drapes, and dozens of families installed air conditioning in their own apartments.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The towers also swayed, particularly during high winds, but tenants eventually became used to the swaying.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] After more tenants with pets moved into the towers, the buildings' trustees banned pets in 1954.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The trustees attempted to evict several pet owners in 1957, and they also filed lawsuits against tenants, with mixed results.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] A tenant of number 880 was killed in a single-apartment fire in 1970.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The buildings remained well-known in the 1970s, even though they were no longer referred to as "the glass houses".
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] By the 1980s, the smaller apartments typically cost $50,000–80,000 apiece, while the larger apartments cost around $120,000 apiece.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] During that decade, the lobbies' opaque glass panes were replaced with an aquamarine-tinted translucent glass.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Between 1990 and 1992, the leaking windows were resealed for $1.5 million, and the facades restored.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Residents hosted a celebration in 1992 to celebrate the buildings' 40th birthday, at which point many tenants said they still loved the buildings.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] By then, nineteen of the original tenants remained, and there were 20 architects living across both buildings.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The towers contained a total of 248 apartments, as some of the original apartments had been combined; the south tower had 90 units, while the north tower had 158 units.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Some of the residents continued to rent out their units.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The towers had higher maintenance costs than the neighboring 900–910 Lake Shore Drive, in part due to number 860–880's small elevators and lack of garbage chutes.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Due to water damage and exterior deterioration over the years, the buildings were restored starting in 2007.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Krueck and Sexton Architects of Chicago were commissioned to oversee the renovation, along with the preservation architects Gunny Harboe Architects.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] They were directed to fix prior renovations that had undermined the historical appearance of the towers, restore the lighting scheme, and renovate the plaza.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The plaza's original stone slabs were cracked, and inadequate waterproofing had caused leaks in the basement, so the slabs were all replaced.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] An additional coat of acrylic paint was applied to the steelwork on the upper floors, while the paint on the first floor of both buildings was completely replaced.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The renovation was completed in December 2009; the cost is variously cited as being between $8 million and $9.2 million.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] When the buildings were constructed, they were controversial because their style was so different from previous skyscrapers.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The architect Frank Lloyd Wright expressed his disappointment that Mies had chosen to create such a design.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] *Architectural Forum* magazine said in 1955 that, while 860–880 Lake Shore Drive was successful, it had inspired several derivatives of markedly lower quality.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The next year, a member of a panel for *Architectural Record* magazine wrote that the complex "is perfect in its proportions, serene in its stand".
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] When *Life* magazine took pictures of the towers in 1957, they were captioned as "animated and inanimate, revealing yet restrained", as perceived from Lake Michigan.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] In 1986, a writer for *Artforum* magazine said the towers and the Farnsworth House were "uncompromised realizations of Mies's rigorous ethic".
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The critic Herbert Muschamp, writing in 1993, regarded the structures as "endlessly complex, acutely sensitive to context" and said that their design embraced the proximity of Lake Michigan.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Also in the late 20th century, the photographer Walter Peterhans and the historian Julius Posener both compared the buildings' I-beams to Gothic structures' architectural details (such as buttresses), which in some cases were purely decorative.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The Society of Architectural Historians praised the lighting scheme in 2007, describing it as an essential part of Mies's design.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Other observers praised the towers' timeless appearance.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Writing about the buildings' architectural impact, Mies's biographer David A.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Spaeth said in 1985 that the buildings had "established a new standard of excellence for the apartment building", as they were among the first entirely steel-and-glass apartment buildings worldwide.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Peterhans said that the towers' construction proved the viability of steel skeletal frames in architecture, contrasting with the masonry facades and smaller windows of earlier buildings.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The American Institute of Architects' (AIA) *Guide to Chicago* regarded the buildings as having had a greater impact on contemporary architects than any of Mies's other works, writing that "the influence of these structures was to pervade much of modern architecture".
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Stern, in 1976, described structures like 860–880 Lake Shore Drive as "a wonderful piece of structure, but not so wonderful as a place to live", saying that they were indistinguishable from office buildings.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Commentators in the 1980s mocked Mies's "less is more" principle, describing the buildings as having a "less-is-a-bore" design, and during that decade, Paul Richard of *The Washington Post* described the I-beams on the facade as being functionally useless.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Blair Kamin wrote in 2014 that the buildings' facades would "seem less elegant and less revolutionary" if it were not for the presence of a masonry building directly to the south, the Lake Shore Athletic Club at 850 North Lake Shore Drive.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Werner Blaser stated in 1999 that the building "opposes [Louis] Sullivan's famous axiom 'form follows function' with the term 'structure'", in that the buildings' superstructures did not at all indicate their interior uses.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The next year, *Architectural Record* magazine described 860–880 Lake Shore Drive as one of the United States' "most famous [architectural] works of the mid-20th century" that were protected as local or national landmarks.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The building was one of the first official landmarks designated in 1958 by the then-new Commission on Chicago Architectural Landmarks, as well as one of the youngest landmarks so designated.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Each building's lobby includes a metallic plaque in honor of this designation, which was dedicated in February 1960.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] After the original landmark commission was repealed, the modern Commission on Chicago Landmarks had considered designating the buildings as Chicago Landmarks starting in 1969, but this was postponed twice due to opposition.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] In a survey in 1980, the majority of residents opposed landmark designation, as they did not want a governmental agency to control future modifications to the buildings.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Even though Chicago Landmark designations could be made without the owners' agreement, the alderman representing the area, Burton Natarus, had recommended that the commission not vote on the landmark designation unless the building's residents supported it.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The city landmark designation was stalled until 1996, when city aldermen rescinded temporary protections from pending landmarks, which had prevented their demolition until their landmark nomination was decided.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The aldermen wished to resolve a legal uncertainty in which the landmark decision (and thus the removal of protections) could occur at any time.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] By then, 104 of 280 households supported landmark protection while 40 households opposed it, and the buildings' trustees narrowly voted to recommend designation.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] After Natarus and other aldermen voted in favor of the designation, 860–880 Lake Shore Drive received Chicago Landmark status on June 10, 1996, which prevented modifications without the commission's approval.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] A square plaque honoring this designation is on a railing near number 860, the south tower.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The towers were the first Mies buildings to be designated as Chicago Landmarks, as well as the first post-World War II buildings to be so designated.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The towers were also added to the National Register of Historic Places (NRHP) in 1980.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Although NRHP listings were generally required to be at least 50 years old, an exception was made for 860–880 Lake Shore Drive because of the towers' architectural significance.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The NRHP designation also did not prevent unauthorized modifications to the structures.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] During the buildings' construction, Edward Duckett of Mies's office created an architectural model of one of the towers, which was displayed on Michigan Avenue as part of a promotional campaign for the development.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Another model, measuring 6 feet (1.8 m) tall, was displayed in New York's Museum of Modern Art (MoMA) in 1950.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] After the buildings were completed, architectural students from around the world came to visit the structures.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] MoMA featured the towers in another exhibition about postwar architecture in 1953, and they were depicted in a book accompanying the exhibition.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] In subsequent years, the buildings were detailed in many modern-architecture books.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Pictures of the towers were also shown at an architecture exhibit at the Sears Tower in the mid-1990s, which featured nine other Chicago buildings.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The towers were showcased in Phyllis Lambert's traveling exhibit *Mies in America* in the early 2000s, and the Art Institute of Chicago also hosted material about them in a 2005 exhibit about post–World War II Chicago architecture.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The buildings received the Twenty-five Year Award from the AIA in 1976, in honor of the longevity of their design.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] In a poll of American architecture experts the same year, at least one expert ranked 860–880 Lake Shore Drive among the best structures in the United States.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] In June 2005, the United States Postal Service included the towers in the commemorative stamp program Masterworks of Modern Architecture, where they were listed as one of the "12 outstanding examples of modern buildings".
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] In celebration of the 2018 Illinois Bicentennial, 860–880 Lake Shore Drive was selected as one of Illinois's 200 Great Places by the AIA's Illinois chapter, AIA Illinois.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] When the towers at 860–880 Lake Shore Drive were completed, they contrasted with the masonry apartment buildings that dominated Chicago at the time, and few buildings anywhere had a similar design.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] After the towers were finished, glass facades became more prevalent across Chicago apartment buildings, while apartments with balconies became less prevalent.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] A myriad of glass-box skyscrapers was also built in the U.S.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Examples of such towers included the Lever House and Seagram Building in New York, as well as the Sears Tower and John Hancock Center in Chicago.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Phyllis Lambert, whose father Samuel Bronfman's company had commissioned the Seagram Building, said that she had recommended that Mies design that building after seeing 860–880 Lake Shore Drive.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Similar designs became commonplace internationally, and *The Wall Street Journal* described their use of prefabricated steel-and-glass exteriors as "one of [Mies's] crowning realizations".
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Mies's disciples copied elements of the design in projects around the world, though the biographer Detlef Mertins wrote that not all of these projects' facades were so closely related to their superstructures.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] When the buildings became Chicago Landmarks in 1996, the Associated Press noted that "all those other high-rises [in other big cities] look like these two".
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The development helped bring attention to Mies's architectural style, The *Chicago Tribune* wrote in 1964 that 860–880 Lake Shore Drive, along with buildings such as Marina City, were examples of a new school of Chicago architecture.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Another writer for the periodical *Universitas* wrote that it "does not seem possible" to create a steel-and-glass building with a simpler design than 860–880 Lake Shore Drive or the Seagram Building.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Paul Gapp of the *Chicago Tribune* wrote in 1981 that 860–880 Lake Shore Drive was among the "internationally famed classics" designed by Mies in Chicago, and Gapp later wrote that the towers had helped make Mies "the 20th Century's single most influential architect".
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Condit wrote that the buildings had influenced modernist architecture in a similar manner to how the Empire State Building and the Woolworth Building had influenced earlier architectural styles.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] After 860–880 Lake Shore Drive, Mies continued to use decorative I-beams in his designs during the rest of his career.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] He duplicated the building's floor grids at 900–910 Lake Shore Drive, across the street; that complex also has a black-painted aluminum facade, referencing the materials used at number 860–880.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] The design of number 860–880's facade was replicated in other skyscrapers that Mies designed during the rest of his career.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Most of his residential buildings did not use protruding I-beams, but his office structures (like the Seagram Building, Toronto-Dominion Centre, and AMA Plaza) did use such a feature.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] Mies also designed the McCormick House in Elmhurst, Illinois, for Robert McCormick Jr., which was inspired by the interior design of 860–880 Lake Shore Drive.
[src:apartment/860-880-lake-shore-drive-apartments] *Luxus Magazine* wrote that the towers' structural grid and facade became "the model for postwar modernist buildings".
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen received royal burgh status from David I of Scotland (1124–1153), which transformed the city economically.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The traditional industries of fishing, paper-making, shipbuilding, and textiles have been overtaken by the oil industry and Aberdeen's seaport.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Heliport is one of the busiest commercial heliports in the world, and the seaport is the largest in the north-east part of Scotland.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] A university town, the city is known for the University of Aberdeen, founded in 1495 as King's College, the fifth oldest university in the English-speaking world and located in Old Aberdeen.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] During the mid-18th to mid-20th centuries, Aberdeen's buildings incorporated locally quarried grey granite, which may sparkle like silver because of its high mica content.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Since the discovery of North Sea oil in 1969, Aberdeen has been known as the offshore **oil capital of Europe**.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Based upon the discovery of prehistoric villages around the mouths of the rivers Dee and Don, the area around Aberdeen is thought to have been settled for at least 6,000 years.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The name given to Aberdeen translates as 'mouth of the river Don', and is recorded as Aberdon in 1172 and Aberden in c.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The first element of the name is the Pictish word *aber* 'river mouth'.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The second element is from the Celtic river goddess Devona.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is usually described as within the historical Pictish territory and became Gaelic-speaking at some time in the medieval period.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Old Aberdeen is the approximate location of Aberdon, the first settlement of Aberdeen; this literally means "the mouth of the Don".
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The Celtic word *aber* means "river mouth", as in modern Welsh (Aberystwyth, Aberdare, Aberbeeg etc.).
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Gaelic name is *Obar Dheathain* (variation: *Obairreadhain*; **obar* presumably being a loan from the earlier Pictish; the Gaelic term is *inbhir*), and in Latin, the Romans referred to the river as *Devana*.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Medieval (or Ecclesiastical) Latin has it as *Aberdonia*.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The local Doric pronunciation, [ˌeːbərˈdin] ⓘ or [ˈeːbərdin] ⓘ (with a long *ay* sound), is frequently rendered *Aiberdeen* or *Aiberdein*.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen area has seen human settlement for at least 8,000 years.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The city began as two separate burghs: Old Aberdeen at the mouth of the river Don; and New Aberdeen, a fishing and trading settlement, where the Denburn waterway entered the river Dee estuary.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The earliest charter was granted by William the Lion in 1179 and confirmed the corporate rights granted by David I.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] In 1214, Aberdeen Burgesses were granted a Royal Charter by Alexander II of Scotland giving them the sole right to form a Guild.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] This body exercised power in the composition of the local council, and the affairs of the town.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The Burgesses of the Guild were an integral part of the council for more than 700 years and played a considerable role in the growth and development of Aberdeen.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] In 1319, the Great Charter of Robert the Bruce transformed Aberdeen into a property-owning and financially independent community.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Granted with it was the nearby Forest of Stocket, whose income formed the basis for the city's Common Good Fund which still benefits Aberdonians.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of Scottish Independence, Aberdeen was under English rule, so Robert the Bruce laid siege to Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308, followed by executing the English garrison.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The city was burned by Edward III of England in 1336, but was rebuilt and extended.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The city was strongly fortified to prevent attacks by neighbouring lords, but the gates were removed by 1770.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's medieval council registers survive from 1398 onwards and are exceptional for their quantity and continuity among surviving Scottish burgh records.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The earliest eight volumes, from 1398 to 1511, have been included in the UNESCO UK Memory of the World Register, and have been edited in a digital edition.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of the Three Kingdoms of 1644 to 1647 the city was plundered by both sides.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] In 1644, it was taken and ransacked by Royalist troops after the Battle of Aberdeen and two years later it was stormed by a Royalist force under the command of the George Gordon, 2nd Marquess of Huntly.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] An outbreak of bubonic plague over 1687 and 1688 killed 8.5% of the population, adding to the economic and demographic damage caused by war.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] In the 18th century, a new Town Hall was built and the first social services appeared with the Aberdeen Infirmary at Woolmanhill in 1739 and the Aberdeen Lunatic Asylum in 1800.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The expensive infrastructure works led to the city becoming bankrupt in 1817 during the Post-Napoleonic depression, an economic downturn immediately after the Napoleonic Wars; but the city's prosperity later recovered.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The increasing economic importance of Aberdeen and the development of the shipbuilding and fishing industries led to the construction of the present harbour including Victoria Dock and the South Breakwater, and the extension of the North Pier.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Gas street lighting arrived in 1824 and an enhanced water supply appeared in 1830 when water was pumped from the Dee to a reservoir in Union Place.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] An underground sewer system replaced open sewers in 1865.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The city absorbed the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee in 1891.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Over the course of World War II Aberdeen was attacked 32 times by the German Luftwaffe.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] One of the most devastating attacks was on Wednesday 21 April 1943 when 29 Luftwaffe Dornier 217s flying from Stavanger, Norway attacked the city between the hours of 22:17 and 23:04.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] A total of 98 civilians and 27 servicemen were killed, along with 12,000 houses damaged, after a mixture of 127 Incendiary, High Explosive and Cluster bombs were dropped on the city in one night.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Two books written in 2018 and 2022 using bombing records held in London identified that unexploded bombs from the 1943 raid were found in the 1950s and 1980s making the bombs dropped 129 in total.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Damage from the raid can still be seen in some parts of Aberdeen.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The arms and banner of the city show three silver towers on red.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] This motif dates from at least the time of Robert the Bruce and represents the buildings that stood on the three hills of medieval Aberdeen: Aberdeen Castle on Castle Hill (today's Castlegate); the city gate on Port Hill; and a church on St Catherine's Hill (now levelled).
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] "Bon Accord" is the motto of the city and is French for "Good Agreement".
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Legend tells that its use dates from a password used by Robert the Bruce during the 14th century Wars of Scottish Independence, when he and his men laid siege to the English-held Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] It is still widely present in the city, throughout street names, business names and the city's Bon Accord shopping mall.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The shield in the coat of arms is supported by two leopards.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] A local magazine is called the "Leopard" and, when Union Bridge was widened in the 20th century, small statues of the creature in a sitting position were cast and placed on top of the railing posts (known locally as Kelly's Cats).
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The city's toast is "Happy to meet, sorry to part, happy to meet again".
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] In 2012, HSBC named Aberdeen as a leading business hub and one of eight 'super cities' spearheading the UK's economy, marking it as the only city in Scotland so designated.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] In 2018, Aberdeen was found to be the best city in the UK to start a business in a study released by card payment firm Paymentsense.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen City is one of 32 council areas of Scotland, administered by Aberdeen City Council.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The council meets at Aberdeen Town House and has its main offices in the adjoining Marischal College.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The civic head and chair of the council is the Lord Provost.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The council area is also divided into 30 community council areas, 29 of which had community councils operating as at August 2024.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The first burgh of Aberdeen, covering just the New Aberdeen area near the mouth of the Dee, was created by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Neighbouring Old Aberdeen to the north was subsequently made a separate burgh in 1489.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The burgh of Aberdeen was governed by a corporation, also known as the town council.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] As Aberdeen grew, the council's powers were inadequate to cater for the needs of the growing urban area.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] A separate police commission was established in 1795 with powers to levy taxes and provide infrastructure ('police' in this context being its older meaning of civic government rather than law enforcement).
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The first police commission was short-lived, but it was resurrected in 1818 after the town council went bankrupt in 1817.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] From 1818 until 1871 there was a dual system of local government, with the town council and police commission having different roles in Aberdeen's administration.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The police commission was eventually abolished in 1871 and its functions absorbed by the town council.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] In 1891 the city boundaries were significantly enlarged, absorbing the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside, plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The act of parliament which expanded the burgh also confirmed that Aberdeen was entitled to be called a city; it had commonly been described as a city prior to that, but (like most Scottish cities) without official recognition.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Following the absorption of Torry in 1891, the city boundaries straddled the counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was made a county of itself in 1899.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] In 1975 the burgh was replaced by the larger City of Aberdeen district within the Grampian region.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Further local government reforms in 1996 replaced the districts and regions created in 1975 with council areas; the pre-1996 City of Aberdeen district became the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] In the Scottish Parliament, the city is represented by three constituencies with different boundaries: Aberdeen Central and Aberdeen Donside are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Deeside and North Kincardine includes the North Kincardine ward of Aberdeenshire Council.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] A further seven MSPs are elected as part of the North East Scotland electoral region.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] In the European Parliament the city was represented by six MEPs as part of the all-inclusive Scotland constituency.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is represented in the Parliament of the United Kingdom by two constituencies, Aberdeen North and Aberdeen South, which are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Being situated between two river mouths, the city has little natural exposure of bedrock.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The small amount of geophysics done, and occasional building-related exposures, combined with small exposures in the banks of the River Don, suggest that it is actually sited on an inlier of Devonian "Old Red" sandstones and silts.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The city extends to 186 km2 (72 sq mi), and includes the former burghs of Old Aberdeen, New Aberdeen, Woodside and the Torry area to the south of River Dee.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] In 2024, this gave the city a population density of 1,249 inhabitants per square kilometre (3,230/sq mi).
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The city is built on many hills, with the original beginnings of the city growing from Castle Hill, St.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] When compared to mainland Europe, Aberdeen is further north than almost all of Denmark and plenty of southern Sweden, being just south of Gothenburg in terms of latitude.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen features an oceanic climate (Köppen *Cfb*), with far milder winter temperatures than one might expect for its northern location.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] However, statistically speaking, it is still the coldest city in the UK.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] During the winter, especially throughout December, the length of the day is very short, averaging 6 hours and 41 minutes between sunrise and sunset at the winter solstice.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] As winter progresses, the length of the day grows fairly quickly, to 8 hours and 20 minutes by the end of January.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Around summer solstice, the days will be around 18 hours long, having 17 hours and 55 minutes between sunrise and sunset.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] During this time of the year marginal nautical twilight lasts the entire night.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Temperatures at this time of year hover around 17.0 °C (62.6 °F) during the day in most of the urban area, though nearer 16.0 °C (60.8 °F) directly on the coast, and around 18.0 to 19.0 °C (64.4 to 66.2 °F) in the westernmost suburbs.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Two weather stations collect climate data for the area, Aberdeen/Dyce Airport, and Craibstone.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Both are about 4+1⁄2 miles (7 km) to the northwest of the city centre, and given that they are in close proximity to each other, exhibit very similar climatic regimes.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Dyce tends to have marginally warmer daytime temperatures year-round owing to its slightly lower elevation, though it is more susceptible to harsh frosts.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The coldest temperature to occur in recent years was −16.8 °C (1.8 °F) during December 2010, while the following winter, Dyce set a new February high-temperature station record on 28 February 2012 of 17.2 °C (63.0 °F), and a new March high temperature record of 21.6 °C (70.9 °F) on 25 March 2012.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The average temperature of the sea ranges from 6.6 °C (43.9 °F) in March to 13.8 °C (56.8 °F) in August.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen locality population estimate is 198,590 (2020).
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] For the wider settlement of Aberdeen including Cove Bay and Dyce, the population estimate is 220,690 (2020).
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] For Aberdeen City council area, the population estimate is 231,780 (2024).
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] In 1396, the population was about 3,000.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The 2011 census showed fewer young people in Aberdeen, with 16.4% under 16, as opposed to the national average of 19.2%.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] According to the 2011 census Aberdeen is 91.9% white, ethnically, 24.7% were born outside Scotland, higher than the national average of 16%.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Of this population, 7.6% were born in other parts of the UK.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] 8.2% of Aberdonians stated to be from an ethnic minority (non-white) in the 2011 census, with 9,519 (4.3%) being Asian, with 3,385 (1.5%) coming from India and 2,187 (1.0%) being Chinese.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The city has around 5,610 (2.6%) residents of African or Caribbean origin, which is a higher percentage than both Glasgow and Edinburgh.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] In the household, there were 97,013 individual dwellings recorded in the city, of which 61% were privately owned, 9% privately rented and 23% rented from the council.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The most popular type of dwellings are apartments which comprise 49% of residences followed by semi-detached at just below 22%.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The median income of a household in the city is £16,813 (the mean income is £20,292) (2005) which places approximately 18% households in the city below the poverty line (defined as 60% of the mean income).
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Conversely, an Aberdeen postcode has the second highest number of millionaires of any postcode in the UK.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The proportion of people residing in Aberdeen born outside the UK was 21.1% in 2022, compared with 15.9% in 2011 and 6.3% in 2001.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Below are the fifteen largest overseas-born groups in Aberdeen according to the 2022 census, alongside the two previous censuses.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Christianity is the main religion practised in the city.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's largest denominations are the Church of Scotland (through the Presbytery of Aberdeen) and the Roman Catholic Church, both with numerous churches across the city, with the Scottish Episcopal Church having the third-largest number.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The census in 2022 showed that Aberdeen has the highest proportion of non-religious residents of any city in Scotland, with 58% of citizens claiming to have no religion.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] In the Middle Ages, the Kirk of St Nicholas was the only burgh kirk and one of Scotland's largest parish churches.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Like a number of other Scottish kirks, it was subdivided after the Reformation, in this case into the East and West churches.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] At that time, the city also was home to houses of the Carmelites (Whitefriars) and Franciscans (Greyfriars).
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The latter survives in modified form as the chapel of Marischal College.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] St Machar's Cathedral was built twenty years after David I (1124–1153) transferred the pre-Reformation diocese from Mortlach in Banffshire to Old Aberdeen in 1137.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Except the episcopate of William Elphinstone (1484–1511), building progressed slowly.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Gavin Dunbar, who followed him in 1518, completed the structure by adding the two western spires and the southern transept.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] It is now a congregation of the Church of Scotland.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Mary's Cathedral is a Roman Catholic cathedral in Gothic style, erected in 1859.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Andrew's Cathedral serves the Scottish Episcopal Church.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] It was constructed in 1817 as Archibald Simpson's first commission and contains a memorial to the consecration of the first bishop of the Episcopal Church in the United States of America, which took place nearby.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] In 1804, St Peter's Church, the first permanent Roman Catholic church in the city after the Reformation was built.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Numerous other Protestant denominations have a presence in Aberdeen.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The Salvation Army citadel on the Castlegate dominates the view of the east end of Union Street.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there is a Unitarian church, established in 1833 and located in Skene Terrace.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Christadelphians have been present in Aberdeen since at least 1844.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Over the years, they have rented space to meet at a number of locations and currently meet in the Inchgarth Community Centre in Garthdee.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Quaker meetinghouse on Crown Street, the only purpose built Friends meeting house in Scotland that is still in use today.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there are a number of Baptist congregations in the city, and Evangelical congregations have been appearing in significant numbers since the late 2000s.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The city also has two meeting houses of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church).
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] There are also four mosques in Aberdeen which serve the Islamic community in the city.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] There is an Orthodox Jewish Synagogue established in 1945.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Thai Buddhist temple located in the Hazelhead area of the city.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] There are no formal Hindu buildings, although there is a fortnightly Hindu religious gathering on the first and third Sunday afternoons at Queens Cross Parish church hall.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen has a small Baháʼí society.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,756 residents aged three and over, 76,650 (35.2%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,760 residents aged three and over, 2,919 (1.3%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Traditionally, Aberdeen was home to fishing, textile mills, shipbuilding and paper-making.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] These industries have been largely replaced.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] High technology developments in the electronics design and development industry, research in agriculture and fishing and the oil industry, which have been largely responsible for Aberdeen's economic growth, are now major parts of Aberdeen's economy.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Until the 1970s, most of Aberdeen's leading industries dated from the 18th century; mainly these were textiles, foundry work, shipbuilding and paper-making, the oldest industry in the city, with paper having been first made there in 1694.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Paper-making has reduced in importance since the closures of Donside Paper Mill in 2001 and the Davidson Mill in 2005 leaving the Stoneywood Paper Mill with a workforce of approximately 500.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Textile production ended in 2004 when Richards of Aberdeen closed.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Grey granite was quarried at Rubislaw quarry for more than 300 years, and used for paving setts, kerb and building stones, and monumental and other ornamental pieces.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen granite was used to build the terraces of the Houses of Parliament and Waterloo Bridge in London.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The current owners have begun pumping 40 years of rainwater from the quarry to develop a heritage centre on the site.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] In-shore fishing was once the predominant industry but was surpassed by deep-sea fisheries, which derived a great impetus from improved technologies throughout the 20th century.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Catches have fallen because of overfishing and the use of the harbour by oil support vessels, and so although still an important fishing port it is now eclipsed by the more northerly ports of Peterhead and Fraserburgh.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The Fisheries Research Services are headquartered in Aberdeen, and there is a marine research laboratory there.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is well regarded for the agricultural and soil research carried out at The James Hutton Institute (formerly the Macaulay Land Use Research Institute), which has close links to the city's two universities.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The Rowett Research Institute is a world-renowned research centre for studies into food and nutrition located in Aberdeen.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] It has produced three Nobel laureates and there is a high concentration of life scientists working in the city.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] As oil reserves in the North Sea decrease, there is an effort to rebrand Aberdeen as the **energy capital of Europe** rather than the oil capital, and there is interest in the development of new energy sources, and technology transfer from oil into renewable energy and other industries is underway.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The "Energetica" initiative led by Scottish Enterprise has been designed to accelerate this process.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has become a major world centre for undersea petroleum technology.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen had been a major maritime centre throughout the 19th century, when a group of local entrepreneurs launched the first steam-powered trawler.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The steam trawling industry expanded and by 1933 Aberdeen was Scotland's top fishing port, employing nearly 3,000 men with 300 vessels sailing from its harbour.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] By the time oil was coming on stream, much of the trawling fleet had relocated to Peterhead.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Geologists had speculated about oil and gas in the North Sea since the middle of the 20th century, but tapping its deep and inhospitable waters was another story.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] With the Middle Eastern oil sheiks becoming more aware of the political and economic power of their oil reserves and government threats of rationing, the industry began to consider the North Sea as a viable source of oil.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Exploration commenced in the 1960s and the first major find in the British sector was in November 1970 in the Forties field, 110 miles (180 km) east of Aberdeen.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] By late 1975, after years of intense construction, the necessary infrastructure was in place.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Oil flowed through the Forties pipeline system directly to the refinery at far-away Grangemouth.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] In 2011, the Centre for Cities named Aberdeen as the best-placed city for growth in Britain, as the country looked to emerge from the recent economic downturn.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] With energy still providing the backbone of the local economy, recent years have seen very large new investment in the North Sea owing to rising oil prices and favourable government tax incentives.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] This has led to several oil majors and independents building new global offices in the city.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Five of Scotland's top ten businesses are based in Aberdeen with a collective turnover of £14 billion, yielding a profit in excess of £2.4 billion.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Alongside this 29 of Scotland's top 100 businesses are located in Aberdeen with an employment rate of 77.9%, making it the second highest UK city for employment.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Figures released in 2016 ranked Aberdeen as having the second highest number of patents processed per person in the UK.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The traditional shopping streets are Union Street and George Street, now complemented by shopping centres, including the Bon Accord Centre and the Trinity Shopping Centre.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] A £190 million retail development, Union Square, reached completion in late September/early October 2009.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Major retail parks away from the city centre include the Berryden Retail Park, the Kittybrewster Retail Park and the Beach Boulevard Retail Park.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Market has been rebuilt twice, but closed in 2020.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] In March 2004, Aberdeen was awarded Fairtrade City status by the Fairtrade Foundation.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's architecture is known for its principal use during the Victorian era of granite, which has led to its local nickname of the Granite City.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] In Castle Street, a continuation eastwards of Union Street, is the new Aberdeen Town House, a very prominent landmark in Aberdeen, built between 1868 and 1873 to a design by Peddie and Kinnear.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Alexander Marshall Mackenzie's extension to Marischal College on Broad Street, opened by King Edward VII in 1906, created the second largest granite building in the world (after the Escorial, Madrid).
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has long been famous for its 45 parks and gardens, and citywide floral displays which include two million roses, eleven million daffodils and three million crocuses.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The city has won the Royal Horticultural Society's Britain in Bloom 'Best City' award ten times, the overall Scotland in Bloom competition twenty times and the large city category every year since 1968.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] However, despite recent spurious reports, Aberdeen has never been banned from the Britain in Bloom competition.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The city won the 2006 Scotland in Bloom "Best City" award along with the International Cities in Bloom award.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The suburb of Dyce also won the Small Towns award.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Duthie Park opened in 1883 on the north bank of the River Dee.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] It was named after and given to the city by Miss Elizabeth Crombie Duthie of Ruthrieston in 1881.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Hazlehead Park, is large and forested, and located on the outskirts of the city.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Johnston Gardens is a small park of one hectare in the west end of the city.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] In 2002, the garden was named the best garden in the British Islands.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Seaton Park, formerly the grounds of a private house, is on the edge of the grounds of St Machar's Cathedral and was acquired for the city in 1947.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has hosted several theatres throughout its history, some of which have been converted or destroyed.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Today, all railway services to the south run via Dundee.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The faster main line from Aberdeen to Perth via Forfar and Strathmore closed in 1967, as a result of the Beeching cuts; the faster main line from Perth to Edinburgh via Glenfarg also closed subsequently in 1970.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] A second station, at Dyce, serves the north of the city centre; it is on the Aberdeen–Inverness line.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] First Aberdeen operates the majority of city bus services, as the successor to Grampian Regional Transport (GRT) and Aberdeen Corporation Tramways.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Secondary operators include Stagecoach Bluebird and Stagecoach South Scotland.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is the global headquarters of parent company FirstGroup, having grown from the GRT Group.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] First is still based at the former Aberdeen Tramways depot on King Street, which has now been redeveloped into a new headquarters and bus depot.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] On 18 April 2025, the "Aberdeen Adventurer" tour bus scheme ran by McGill's Bus Services was launched with 10 stops around the city on a 75-minute loop.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Stops include King's College, Pittodrie Stadium and the Aberdeen Art Gallery with the service due to end on 20 September 2026.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen International Airport (ABZ), sited in Dyce in the north of the city, serves domestic and international destinations in France, the Netherlands, Spain, Ireland and Scandinavian countries.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The heliport, which serves the oil industry and rescue services, is one of the world's busiest commercial heliports.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is connected to the UK's National Cycle Network; it has a track to the south, connecting to cities including Dundee and Edinburgh, and one to the north that forks about 10 miles (15 km) from the city into two different tracks heading to Inverness and Fraserburgh respectively.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Two popular shared-use paths, along old railway lines, are the Deeside Way to Banchory (which will eventually connect to Ballater) and the Formartine and Buchan Way to Ellon, both used by a mixture of cyclists, walkers and occasionally horses.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] In May 2026, a self-service e-bike hire scheme was introduced in Aberdeen, operated by Voi Technology.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Some 350 bikes are available on a pay-as-you-go basis.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The scheme replaced an earlier bike hire scheme which was operated between 2022 and 2024 by *The Big Issue* and Sharebike but which was scrapped because of funding issues as well as vandalism.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Harbour is important as the largest in the north of Scotland and serves the ferry route to Orkney and Shetland.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Established in 1136, the harbour has been referred to as the "oldest business in Britain".
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The Dee Estuary, Aberdeen's harbour, started out as a fishing port, moving on to steam trawlers and serving the oil industry; it is now a major port of departure for the Baltic and Scandinavia.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has two universities, the ancient University of Aberdeen, and Robert Gordon University, a modern university often referred to as RGU.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has a high proportion of students of 11.5%, higher than the national average of 7%.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen began as King's College, Aberdeen, which was founded in 1495 by William Elphinstone (1431–1514), Bishop of Aberdeen and Chancellor of Scotland.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Marischal College, a separate institution, was founded in New Aberdeen by George Keith, fifth Earl Marischal of Scotland in 1593.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] These institutions were merged by the Universities (Scotland) Act 1858 to form the University of Aberdeen.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The university is the fifth oldest in the English-speaking world and offers degrees in a full range of disciplines.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Its main campus is in Old Aberdeen in the north of the city and it currently has approximately 14,000 students.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The university's debating society is the oldest in Scotland, founded in 1848 as the King's College Debating Society.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Today, Aberdeen is consistently ranked among the top 200 universities in the world and is ranked within the top 20 universities in the United Kingdom.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was also named the 2019 Scottish University of the Year by The Times and Sunday Times Good University Guide.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] In early 2022, Aberdeen opened the Science Teaching Hub.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Robert Gordon's College (originally Robert Gordon's Hospital) was founded in 1750 by the merchant Robert Gordon, grandson of the map maker Robert Gordon of Straloch, and was further endowed in 1816 by Alexander Simpson of Collyhill.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Originally devoted to the instruction and maintenance of the sons of poor burgesses of guild and trade in the city, it was reorganised in 1881 as a day and night school for secondary and technical education.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] In 1903, the vocational education component of the college was designated a Central Institution and was renamed as the Robert Gordon Institute of Technology in 1965.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] In 1992, university status was awarded and it became Robert Gordon University.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The university has expanded and developed significantly in recent years, and was named Best Modern University in the UK for 2012 by *The Sunday Times*.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] It was previously *The Sunday Times* Scottish University of the Year for 2011, primarily because of its record on graduate employment.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is also home to two artistic schools: Gray's School of Art, founded in 1886, which is one of the oldest established colleges of art in the UK.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Scott Sutherland School of Architecture and Built Environment, was one of the first architectural schools to have its training courses recognised by the Royal Institute of British Architects.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Both are now part of Robert Gordon University and are based at its Garthdee campus.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] North East Scotland College has several campuses in the city and offers a wide variety of part-time and full-time courses leading to several different qualifications in science.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Agricultural College is based just outside Aberdeen, on the Craibstone Estate.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] This is situated beside the roundabout for Aberdeen Airport on the A96.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The college provides three services—Learning, Research and Consultancy.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The college features many land-based courses such as Agriculture, Countryside Management, Sustainable Environmental Management and Rural Business Management.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] There are a variety of courses from diplomas to master's degrees.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The Marine Laboratory Aberdeen, which specialises in fisheries, Macaulay Land Use Research Institute (soil science), and the Rowett Research Institute (animal nutrition) are some other higher education institutions.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen College of Performing Arts also provides full-time Drama and Musical Theatre training at Further Education level.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] There are currently 15 secondary schools and 54 primary schools which are run by the city council.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] There are a number of private schools in Aberdeen: Robert Gordon's College, Albyn School, St Margaret's School for Girls, the International School of Aberdeen and a Waldorf/Steiner School.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] State secondary schools in Aberdeen include Aberdeen Grammar School, Bridge of Don Academy, Bucksburn Academy, Cults Academy, Dyce Academy, Harlaw Academy, Hazlehead Academy, Lochside Academy, Northfield Academy, Oldmachar Academy and St Machar Academy.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p01] Independent primary and secondary schools in Aberdeen include Albyn School, Robert Gordon's College, St Margaret's School for Girls, and the International School of Aberdeen.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The city has a wide range of cultural activities, amenities, and museums, and is regularly visited by Scotland's National Arts Companies.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] It was awarded the Nicholson Trophy for the best-kept town at the Britain in Bloom contest in 1975.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery houses a collection of Impressionist, Victorian, Scottish and 20th-century British paintings as well as collections of silver and glass.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] It also includes The Alexander Macdonald Bequest, a collection of late 19th-century works donated by the museum's first benefactor and a constantly changing collection of contemporary work and regular visiting exhibitions.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery reopened in 2019 after a four-year refurbishment costing £34.6m.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Maritime Museum, located in Shiprow, tells the story of Aberdeen's links with the sea from the days of sail and clipper ships to the latest oil and gas exploration technology.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] It includes an 8.5-metre-high (28 ft) model of the Murchison oil production platform and a 19th-century assembly taken from Rattray Head lighthouse Provost Ross' House is the second oldest dwelling house in the city.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] It was built in 1593 and became the residence of Provost John Ross of Arnage in 1702.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The house retains some original medieval features, including a kitchen, fireplaces and beam-and-board ceilings.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The Gordon Highlanders Museum tells the story of one of Scotland's best known regiments.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Provost Skene's House on Flourmill Lane dates from 1545 and is the oldest surviving townhouse in the city.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] It reopened in October 2021 after significant refurbishment costing £3.8m.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] One of the new exhibitions is a Hall of Heroes featuring 100 Aberdonians who have made a significant contribution to the city.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The Tollbooth Museum on the Castlegate (currently closed to visitors) is a former jail, which first opened as a public museum in 1995.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Treasure Hub is a storage facility for Aberdeen Museums and Galleries containing over 100,000 items.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The store is open for infrequent tours, for example as part of Doors Open Day.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Marischal Museum holds the principal collections of the University of Aberdeen, comprising some 80,000 items in the areas of fine art, Scottish history and archaeology, and European, Mediterranean and Near Eastern archaeology.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The permanent displays and reference collections are augmented by regular temporary exhibitions, and since its closure to the public it now has a virtual online presence It closed to the public in 2008.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The King's Museum acts as the main museum of the university now.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Student Show, performed annually without interruption since 1921, under the auspices of the Aberdeen Students' Charities Campaign, is the longest-running of its kind in the United Kingdom.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] It is written, produced and performed by students and graduates of Aberdeen's universities and higher education institutions.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Since 1929—other than on a handful of occasions—it has been staged at His Majesty's Theatre.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] National festivals which visited Aberdeen in 2012 included the British Science Festival in September, hosted by the University of Aberdeen but with events also taking place at Robert Gordon University and at other venues across the city.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] In February 2012 the University of Aberdeen also hosted the Inter Varsity Folk Dance Festival, the longest-running folk festival in the United Kingdom.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Spectra, an annual light festival hosted in different locations across the city.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Nuart, a festival showcasing street art around the city.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] In 2020, the WayWORD Festival was launched by the University of Aberdeen WORD centre for creative writing.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] This yearly programme celebrates the arts through readings, performances, workshops and discussion panels.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] There have been many notable headliners including Val McDermid, Irvine Welsh and Douglas Stuart (writer).
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Galas are held annually throughout the city, the most notable being the Culter Gala, which is usually held on the last Saturday of May.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The local dialect of Lowland Scots is often known as Doric and is spoken not just in the city, but across the northeast of Scotland.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] It differs somewhat from other Scots dialects: most noticeable are the pronunciation "f" for what is normally written "wh" and "ee" for what in standard English would usually be written "oo" (Scots "ui").
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Every year the annual Doric Festival takes place in Aberdeenshire to celebrate the history of the north-east's language.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Scotland's oldest newspaper the *Press and Journal*, a local and regional newspaper first published in 1747.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The *Press and Journal* and its sister paper the tabloid *Evening Express* are printed six days a week by Aberdeen Journals.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] There was one free newspaper, the *Aberdeen Citizen*.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] BBC Scotland has a network studio production base in the city's Beechgrove area, and BBC Aberdeen produces *The Beechgrove Potting Shed* for radio while Tern Television produces *The Beechgrove Garden*.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The city is also home to STV North (formerly Grampian Television), which produces the regional news programmes such as *STV News at Six*, as well as local commercials.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The station, based at Craigshaw Business Park in Tullos, was based at larger studios in Queens Cross from September 1961 until June 2003.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Music venues include the Music Hall and the P&J Live.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen region has given its name to a number of dishes, including the Aberdeen buttery (also known as "rowie") and Aberdeen Sausage.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] In 2015, a study was published in The Scotsman which analysed the presence of branded fast food outlets in Scotland.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Of the ten towns and cities analysed, Aberdeen was found to have the lowest per capita concentration, with just 0.12 stores per 1,000 inhabitants.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The public health service in Scotland, NHS Scotland provides for the people of Aberdeen through the NHS Grampian health board.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Albyn Hospital is a private hospital located in the west end of the city.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen City Council is responsible for city-owned infrastructure which is paid for by a mixture of Council Tax and income from the Scottish Government.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure and services run by the council include: nursery, primary and secondary education, roads, clearing snow in winter, city wardens, maintaining parks, refuse collection, economic development, public analyst, public mortuary, street cleaning and street lighting.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure in private hands includes electricity, gas and telecoms.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Water and sewerage services are provided by Scottish Water.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The first ever recorded game of football, was outlined by teacher David Wedderburn in his book "Vocabula" written in 1633, during his time teaching at Aberdeen Grammar School.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] There is one Aberdeen-based football club in the SPFL.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] (The Dons) play in the Scottish Premiership at Pittodrie Stadium.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The club won the European Cup Winners Cup and the European Super Cup in 1983, the Scottish Premier League Championship four times (1955, 1980, 1984 and 1985), and the Scottish Cup eight times (1947, 1970, 1982, 1983, 1984, 1986, 1990 and 2025).
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of Alex Ferguson, Aberdeen was a major force in British football during the 1980s.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of McInnes the team won the 2014 Scottish League Cup and followed it up with a second-place league finish for the first time in more than 20 years in the following season.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] But it was over the last few seasons that results stagnated and McInnes was replaced by former Aberdeen and Newcastle player Stephen Glass.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Cove Rangers, as of season 2024-25 play in League One, at the Balmoral Stadium in the suburb of Cove Bay.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Cove won the Highland Football League championship in 2001, 2008, 2009, 2013 and 2019, winning the League Two play-offs in 2019 and earning promotion.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] At the point at which the 2019/20 League Two season was curtailed due to the COVID-19 pandemic, Cove were sitting top of the League Two table and were promoted as Champions.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Other local teams include Banks o'Dee who play at Spain Park in the Highland Football League and members of the SJFA North Region; Culter, Dyce, Stoneywood Parkvale, Glentanar, Sunnybank Hall Russell United, Bridge of Don Thistle and Hermes.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen hosted Caledonia Reds, a Scottish rugby team, before they merged with the Glasgow Warriors in 1998.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] In 2005 the President of the SRU said it was hoped eventually to establish a professional team in Aberdeen.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] In November 2008 the city hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Canada, with Scotland winning 41–0.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] In November 2010 the city once again hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Samoa, with Scotland winning 19–16.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Warriors rugby league team play in the Rugby League Conference Division One.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The Warriors also run Under 15's and 17's teams.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Grammar School won the Saltire Schools Cup in 2011.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The Royal Aberdeen Golf Club, founded in 1780 is the sixth oldest golf club in the world, and hosted the Senior British Open in 2005, and the amateur team event the Walker Cup in 2011.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Royal Aberdeen also hosted the Scottish Open in 2014, won by Justin Rose.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The club has a second course, and there are public golf courses at Auchmill, Balnagask, Hazlehead and King's Links.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] There are new courses planned for the area, including world-class facilities with major financial backing, the city and shire are set to become important in golf tourism.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] In Summer 2012, Donald Trump opened a new state of the art golf course at Menie, just north of the city, as the Trump International Golf Links, Scotland.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Ice hockey in Aberdeen boasts a history that began in the early 20th century.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Glaciarium on Forbesfield Road became a hub for games, featuring teams like the Grammar School Former Pupils and the Aberdeen Ice Hockey Club.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] However, the sport all but died out with the onset of WW1.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The sport was revived in the city with the opening of the Linx Ice Arena in 1992.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Lynx plays in the Scottish National League and is based at the Linx Ice Arena.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Founded in 2005, they won back to back regular season titles in 2022-23 and 2023–24 and won the play-off championship in 2015-16 and again in 2024–25.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] They regularly sell out home games and are the second best supported sports team in the city after Aberdeen FC.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The City of Aberdeen Swim Team (COAST) was based in Northfield swimming pool, but since the opening of the Aberdeen Aquatics Centre in 2014, it is now based there, as it has a 50 m pool as opposed to the 25 m pool at Northfield.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The team comprises several smaller swimming clubs and has enjoyed success throughout Scotland and in international competitions.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Three of the team's swimmers qualified for the 2006 Commonwealth Games.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] There are four boat clubs that row on the River Dee: Aberdeen Boat Club (ABC), Aberdeen Schools Rowing Association (ASRA), Aberdeen University Boat Club (AUBC) and Robert Gordon University Boat Club (RGUBC).
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The city has one national league side, Stoneywood-Dyce.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Local "Grades" cricket has been played in Aberdeen since 1884.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeenshire were the 2009 and 2014 Scottish National Premier League and Scottish Cup Champions.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen University Shinty Club (Scottish Gaelic: Club Camanachd Oilthigh Obar Dheathain) is the oldest constituted shinty club in the world, dating back to 1861.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The city council operates public tennis courts in various parks including an indoor tennis centre at Westburn Park.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The Beach Leisure Centre is home to a climbing wall, gymnasium and a swimming pool.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] There are numerous swimming pools dotted around the city notably the largest, the Bon Accord Baths which closed down in 2008.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] In common with many other major towns and cities in the UK, Aberdeen has an active roller derby league, Granite City Roller Derby.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Roughnecks American football club is a new team that started in 2012 and is the first team that Aberdeen has witnessed since the Granite City Oilers that began in 1986 and were wound up in the mid-1990s.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Oilers Floorball Club was founded in 2007.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The club initially attracted a range of experienced Scandinavian and other European players who were studying in Aberdeen.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Since their formation, Aberdeen Oilers have played in the British Floorball Northern League and went on to win the league in the 2008/09 season.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The club played a major role in setting up a ladies league in Scotland.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The Oilers' ladies team ended up second in the first ladies league season (2008/09).
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] One of the earliest known disasters is the Storegga Slide in the mesolithic period in 6225–6170 BCE which caused tsunami waves to hit North sea coastal areas, with wave heights of 3-6 meters in the north east Scotland areas.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] In 1876, the River Dee ferryboat disaster took place when 32 people drowned in the mouth of the River Dee.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The 20th century includes a World War II disaster when in 1943, a Luftwaffe raid dropped 129 bombs on Aberdeen resulting in 125 deaths..
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] In 1964, a typhoid outbreak occurred with 400 cases and three fatalities.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] In 1983, the Aberdeen taxi driver George Murdoch was killed, the murder case is unsolved.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] In modern time, accidents have been related with offshore drilling.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] In 1988, the oil platform Piper Alpha, located 190 km north-east of Aberdeen, exploded and collapsed, killing 165.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The accident is the worst ever offshore oil and gas disaster in terms of lives lost.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Hazlehead Park contains a memorial to the crew. .
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] In 1995, the Bristow Helicopters Flight 56C was struck by lightning and emergency landed in the sea.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] The 18 crew and passengers on board survived.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] In 2009, the Bond Offshore Helicopters Flight 85N crashed 20 km north-east of Peterhead, while returning from an oil platform to Aberdeen Airport.
[src:apartment/aberdeen-p02] Johnston Gardens contains a memorial to the deceased.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] In economics, an **absentee landlord** is a person who owns and rents out a profit-earning property, but does not live within the property's local economic region.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] The term "absentee ownership" was popularised by economist Thorstein Veblen's 1923 book of the same name, *Absentee Ownership*.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] However, some jurisdictions seek to extract money from absentee owners by taxing land.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] Absentee ownership has sometimes put the absentee owners at risk of loss.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] Absentee landlords were a highly significant issue in the history of Ireland.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] In the 16th and 17th centuries, much of Ireland's land was confiscated from Catholic landowners by the Crown during the plantations of Ireland and granted to Protestant settlers from Great Britain.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] Many of these settlers and their descendants eventually returned to Britain while continuing to own their Irish estates, renting them out to local tenants.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] In 1782, Irish Patriot Party politician Henry Grattan claimed that absentee landlords earned approximately £800,000 *per annum* from their Irish estates and attempted to impose an additional tax on remittances sent to them.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] By the 1800s, resentment towards these landlords grew, as not only were the absentee landlords all Protestant, but the goods produced on their estates were primarily exported to foreign markets.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] This system became particularly detrimental to the Irish public during the Great Famine, when, despite Ireland becoming a net importer of food, millions either died of starvation or disease or emigrated elsewhere.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] In the years following the famine, the Irish National Land League engaged in the Land War to address the issue of absentee landlords in Ireland.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] The issue was one of the contributing factors that led to the Irish revolutionary period, although it had largely been resolved by the British government in 1903 through the Land Acts.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] An absentee landlord crisis was a key factor in Prince Edward Island's decision to become a part of Canada when the idea of Confederation was proposed in 1867.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] In the mid-1760s, a survey team divided the Island into 67 lots.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] On July 1, 1767, these properties were allocated to associates of George III by means of a lottery.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] Ownership of the land remained in the hands of British-based landlords, angering settlers on the island who were unable to gain title to land on which they worked and lived.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] Significant rent charges (to absentee landlords) created further anger.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] The land had been given to the absentee landlords with a number of conditions attached regarding upkeep and settlement terms; many of these conditions were not satisfied.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] The settlers spent decades trying to convince the Crown to confiscate the lots, however the descendants of the original owners generally held significant levels of influence with Crown officials and refused to give up the land.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] In 1853, the colonial government on the island passed the Land Purchase Act, which empowered them to purchase lands from those owners who were willing to sell, and then resell the land to settlers for low prices.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] This scheme collapsed when the colonial government ran short of money to continue with the purchases.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] Many of these lands also were fertile, and were some of the key factors to sustaining Prince Edward Island's economy.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] In 1864, the colonial government saw union with Canada as a possible solution to the landlord crisis.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] This followed a rent strike and riots on the island.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] At the Charlottetown Conference, delegates proposed a fund to purchase landlords' holdings if the Island joined Confederation.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] Several weeks later at the Quebec Conference this offer was withdrawn.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] The Island resolved not to enter Confederation as a result.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] The government refused offers from the other provinces and relented in 1873 only after the local economy was pushed near to collapse.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] Under the terms of union, Canada agreed to provide the Island with an $800 000 fund to purchase the remaining absentee holdings.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] In 1875, the *Land Purchase Act* was enacted to force owners of the large estates to sell their holdings to the provincial government.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] The Island's experience with absentee landlords affects its land ownership laws to this day.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] Non-residents are not permitted to purchase land in excess of two hectares without prior approval from the cabinet.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] In 2009 an American was fined $29,000 for contravening these laws.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] The Ottoman Empire embarked on a systematic land reform program in the second half of the 19th century.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] Two of the new laws were the 1858 land registration law and the 1873 land emancipation act.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] Prior to 1858, land in Palestine, then a part of the Ottoman Empire since 1516, was cultivated or occupied mainly by peasants.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] Land ownership was regulated by people living on the land according to customs and traditions.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] Usually, the land was communally owned by village residents, though land could be owned by individuals or families.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] In 1858 the Ottoman Empire introduced *The Ottoman Land Code of 1858*, requiring landowners to register ownership.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] The reasons behind the law were twofold.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] (1) to increase tax revenue, and (2) to exercise greater state control over the area.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] The registration process itself was open to misregistration and manipulation.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] Land collectively owned by village residents ended up registered to one villager, and merchants and local Ottoman administrators took the opportunity to register large areas of land to their own name.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] The result was land that became the legal property of people who had never lived on the land, while the peasants, having lived there for generations, retained possession, but became tenants of absentee owners.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] The 1856 Emancipation Reform Decree and 1869 citizenship law was interpreted as giving Jews the right to own land in Ottoman Syria under their own name.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] This 1873 secular land reform/civil rights law was popularly confused with religious law and it was held as a "humiliation to Islam that Jews should own a part of the Muslim Ummah".
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] The confusion between religious and secular law made the laws (ended in 1873) against Jewish ownership of land 'religious laws'.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] Over the course of the next decades land became increasingly concentrated on fewer hands; the peasants continued to work on the land, giving landlords a share of the harvest.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] This led to both an increased level of Palestinian nationalism as well as civil unrest.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] At the same time the area witnessed an increased flow of Jewish immigrants who did not restrict themselves to the cities where their concentration offered some protection from persecution.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] These new Jews came hoping to create a new future in what they regarded as the homeland of their ancestors.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] Organizations created to aid the Jewish migration to Palestine also bought land from absentee landowners.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] Jewish immigrants then settled on the land, sometimes replacing peasants already living there.
[src:apartment/absentee-landlords] A steady arrival of Jewish immigrants from 1882 led to several peasant insurgencies, recorded from as early as 1884–1886.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Adaptive reuse is defined as the aesthetic process that adapts buildings for new uses while retaining their historic features.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Using an adaptive reuse model can prolong a building's life, from cradle-to-grave, by retaining all or most of the building system, including the structure, the shell and even the interior materials.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] This type of revitalization is not restricted to buildings of historic significance and can be a strategy adopted in the case of obsolete buildings.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Typically categorised under *economic*, *social*, *cultural and historical*, and *environmental benefits*.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Some urban planners see adaptive reuse as an effective way of reducing urban sprawl and environmental impact.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] According to Yung and Chan, "adaptive reuse is a new kind of maintainable rebirth of city, as it covers the building's lifetime and evades destruction waste, encourages recycles of the embodied dynamism and also delivers substantial social and economic profits to the world".
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Revitalizing the existing built fabric by finding a new use or purpose for obsolete buildings can be a wonderful resource to a community by "keeping neighborhoods occupied and vital".
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] The reuse of older vacant buildings for other purposes forms a very important aspect of any urban regeneration scheme.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Adopting the adaptive reuse approach for the redevelopment of older vacant buildings provides added benefits to the regeneration of an urban area in a sustainable way, through transforming these buildings into usable and accessible units.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] The adaptive reuse strategy would also enable the local authority and owners of older vacant buildings in urban areas to minimize their economic, social and environmental costs, in a quest for a continued urban expansion and development.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Built heritage conservation through adaptive reuse could therefore be used to promote sustainable historical and cultural development of urban areas.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Parameters to prioritise historical buildings for adaptive reuse and the characterisation of adaptive reuse stakeholders are also noted.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Typically categorised under *building regulatory requirements and governance*, *financial*, *management*, and *complexities and uncertainties challenges*.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] According to Chusid's "urban ore" concept, existing buildings that are fast approaching dilapidation or disuse are a "mine of raw materials for new projects".
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Shen and Langston built upon Chusid's idea and said that "an even more effective solution than raw material recovery is adaptive reuse".
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] They studied that "a huge focus on economic factors alone has led to the destruction of buildings well short of their physical lives".
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Shen and Langston developed an integrated model for the assessment of adaptive reuse potential (ARP model) in 2008 by comparing case studies of one urban and one non-urban setting.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] The basis of this model lies in that "opportunity rises and falls within the confines of a negative exponential decay function linked to a building's physical life expectancy".
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] According to their study, a building reaches its maximum potential for adaptive reuse at a point when the building's age and its useful life merge or meet.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] At this point, the building's adaptive reuse potential is either an upward curve or a downward curve which can determine whether the potential is high, medium or low.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] The adaptive reuse potential calculator establishes a "predicted useful life" of a building by considering a series of physical, economic, functional, technological, social, legal and political characteristics.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] These characteristics are used to derive an "annual obsolescence rate" and "environmental obsolescence".
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] These outcomes are necessary to determine an optimum point at which adaptive reuse intervention should occur.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] An algorithm based on a standard decay (negative exponential) curve produces an index of reuse potential (known as the ARP score) and is expressed as a percentage.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] This decay curve in buildings can be used to establish an ARP score, which is expressed in percentage.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Cities can rank their existing buildings as per their adaptive reuse potential and this data can be used by government authorities at any point in time.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] An adaptive reuse score of 50% or above is considered high.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Anything between that range is considered moderate.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Shen and Langston devised this concept of ARP as "rising from zero to its maximum score at the point of its useful life, and then falling back to zero as it approaches physical life".
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] AdaptSTAR is a 2013 model to facilitate adaptive reuse projects and has also been shown to be a good predictor of a successful project along with the ARP model.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] A 2023 literature review identified some key factors for whether an adaptive reuse project would be a success.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Structural factors emphasize the importance of extending the lifespan of the building among other practical factors.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Cultural factors focus on the ability of the building to contribute to a sense of place and community pride, attracting the interest of the community in participating in its new phase of life, while improving the quality of life of its users.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Adaptive reuse projects are, in many ways, different from conventional new construction projects and must be planned and managed differently.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Before starting an adaptive reuse project and even considering refurbishment, it is important that the condition of the existing building is thoroughly assessed.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] A condition assessment primarily inspects a building's structural integrity, roofing, masonry, plaster, wood-work, tiling and the mechanical, electrical and plumbing systems.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] The in-depth inspection of buildings can be expensive.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Nevertheless, building condition assessment is critical to the success of an adaptive reuse project and must not be avoided at any cost because this expense is insignificant relative to the injury or loss of life that a building failure might cause.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] One logical reason, as explained by the American Society of Civil Engineers, is that even a very well constructed building could undergo serious deterioration and eventually failure, if proper maintenance is not performed in the operational phase of the building.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] The direct inspection of the structural system is required to a certain degree which is decided by the judgement of an experienced civil engineer.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Sometimes, built assets cannot be considered suitable for adaptive reuse, simply because of the constraints of their built form or the condition that they are in.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Former jails and mid-1900s low-rise apartments that have low floor area ratios (FAR) and which may be in some of the cities' prime locations have tended to be seen as less profitable for adaptive reuse.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] After identifying the stability and soundness of a building, it is important to survey the neighborhood to find the potential use and function of the adaptive reuse project for that segment of the market or region that the building owners wish to attract.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] In many cases, an adaptive reuse project might help stabilize a neighborhood which may be otherwise decaying or be at a threat of vandalism.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] This upward trend may create lucrative rent opportunities for building owners and dwellers of the neighborhood.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] This survey can be in the form of a physical inspection of the neighborhood and/or a detailed study of the zoning map of that region.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Pedestrian activity, presence of sidewalks, street lights, benches and public parks and the presence of well-occupied shops and buildings can tell us a lot about neighborhoods.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] After the neighborhood has been established to be stable and safe and free of any infringing decay, the next step is to determine what amenities it has to offer in terms of roadways, public transportation, shopping and eating, hospitals, schools and libraries.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] The decision to reuse or demolish built assets is driven by economic considerations such as development costs, project costs, investment returns and market.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] The economic costs differ from project to project and a growing body of research suggests that adaptive reuse is often cost-effective than demolition and new construction.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Adaptive reuse projects have the potential to work in phases or parts.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] A major advantage of renovating an existing building is that a refurbished portion of the building becomes suitable for occupancy before completion of the whole project.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] This provides as a huge advantage for private developers as it keeps the cash inflow while the rest of the project undergoes construction.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Keeping in mind the conclusions from structural and architectural survey, neighborhood survey and marketing survey, a budget is prepared.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Building owners or developers can approach any of the financing sources such as insurance companies, foundations and funds, savings banks, building loan societies, endowment funds, and Real estate investment trusts.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] According to Bullen and Love in 2011, the adaptive reuse decision making was fundamentally driven by a "desire for short-term profits".
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Building owners consider the life expectancy of built assets, their energy and environmental performance and the high operating costs which may appear due to poor mechanical equipment, services, building materials and construction.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Developers saw a thorough potential in saving groundwork and excavation costs by using an adaptive reuse model for their property.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Additionally, they thought that "in Central Business District locations, built assets are an attractive investment option for reuse projects, as premium prices and rents can be obtained for an office space".
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] The highest rents often go to remodeled buildings with "high-quality finishes" and good aesthetics that are not too expensive to operate and maintain.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Governments sometimes provide support and incentives for adaptive reuse of built assets.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] This could include flexibility in the building codes and more plot ratio bonuses among other ways of encouraging innovative adaptive reuse designs.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] The existing building codes and regulations for fire safety and building access to people with disabilities can make it difficult to adaptively reuse some older buildings.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Tax incentives or grants from governments on donors also makes adaptive reuse more viable when available.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] The United States' National Historic Preservation Act of 1966, for example, established matching grants-in-aid, obtained through state historic preservation offices, that can be used for the acquisition and restoration of properties listed in the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] In most adaptive reuse projects, it is the architect who is the leader with the imagination of how an abandoned warehouse can become an office building or an abandoned hospital a condominium.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Since the architect has a deep involvement in the success of a project, they must perform their work under a clearly defined contract.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Under this contract, the architect and the owner are under the obligation of the contract and must abide by it.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Progress of design, site visits and evaluation are some of the basic actions that the architect performs under this contract.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] There are different types of contracts, ranging from a fixed fee contract, percentage of construction cost contract and fee plus expenses contract.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] All stakeholders may collectively decide on the most suitable type of contract for the project.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Before the architect and engineer begin the final designing for the building, they make a thorough structural, mechanical and architectural survey of the existing building.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] The architect and engineer may look for signs of cracking of masonry wall or the settling of basement floors or upper floors which direct them to a problem in the foundation.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] These signs can also be detected from window sills and cornices.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Appropriate survey instruments such as plumb bobs and spirit levels are recommended for use instead of a naked eye inspection.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] If the problem seems too severe, a test boring may reveal the cause of the problem.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Additionally, the building code should be examined for fireproofing requirements.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Analyzing the structural strength requires expertise and is one of the most crucial in terms of occupant safety.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] On-site inspection along with a study of existing floor plans can help engineers determine the structural stability.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] In some case, when the building drawings may not be available, engineers may have to scrape off the plaster to reveal the underlying structure.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Wooden members of the structural system should be especially checked for rot or termite infestation.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Iron or steel must be checked for corrosion and loose bearings or bolting.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Additional future dead and live loads must be kept in mind while designing with the structural strength of the existing building.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] The floor system in old buildings is usually strong enough to satisfy present codes.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] If not, additional supporting members may be necessary.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] The floor and ceiling height should be able to accommodate additional stairways, vertical plumbing, electrical and HVAC.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] In some cases, an elevator may have to be installed.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] The building envelope should be examined thoroughly for cracks, watertightness (infiltration or leaks) and mortar joints.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] It is important to examine these exterior walls for future fenestration and air conditioning ducts.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Older building roofing systems generally comprise the roof, parapets and cornices.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Projecting metal cornices are subject to corrosion.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Parapets may be subject to cracks and degrading mortar joints.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] A careful examination of the top-floor ceiling may reveal water leakage.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] The stairway requirement for a building should be derived from present-day building codes for fire and safety.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Strategic placement of new staircases and layout for maximum access should be done in order to maximize space utility and minimize the burden on the structural system.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Redesigning the existing building for new use must accommodate energy conservation strategies.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Some of the most important methods of energy conservation are, reducing heating and cooling loads through building envelopes, maximizing natural ventilation potential, using daylighting and energy efficient lighting fixtures.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] A building's envelope protects it from the external weather conditions.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] An exposed roof is the greatest source of heat loss during cold months and heat gains during hot months.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Roof insulation can help with extreme climate conditions.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] If the bottom floor is a concrete floor slab on grade or built over a crawl space, insulation should be considered.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] The fenestration in an external wall assembly are often the biggest sources of energy losses through conduction, radiation and infiltration.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Building owners and developers can take the potential advantage of adaptive reuse by taking away components from unused buildings and then repair, reuse or recycle its constituent parts.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Disassembly is a form of recovering target products and plays a key role to maximize the efficiency of an adaptive reuse project.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] This disassembly planning sequence aims to reduce the environmental impacts caused due to demolition using a "rule-base recursive analysis system" with practical and viable solutions.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] As a comparatively young country, adaptive reuse is not the norm in Canada, where redevelopment has typically meant demolition and building anew.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Calgary and Edmonton are particularly known for their pro-demolition culture, but they are not unique in this regard.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] However, since the 1990s, adaptive use has gained traction.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] The conversion of former railway-centred warehouse districts to residential and commercial uses has occurred in Edmonton, Calgary, Saskatoon, Regina, and Winnipeg.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] In 2025, the planned demolition of the old Provincial Museum Building in Edmonton was cancelled amid community opposition with the government soliciting proposals for potential adaptive reuse of the building.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] In Calgary, a city program to transform vacant office towers to apartments launched in 2021 had supported the construction of 2,450 apartments in the city's downtown neighbourhood as of 2025, including in the former Petrofina building.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Marie, an ongoing project to convert the derelict St.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Mary's Paper mill into a mixed-use cultural and tourism hub.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Urban waterfronts, historically used as points for industrial production and transport, became popular as residences and mixed use.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] The greatest value of the adaptive use movement is characterized by the hundreds of abandoned schools, factories, hotels, warehouses and military posts that have been adapted for use as affordable housing, office buildings, as well as commercial, civic, educational and recreational centers.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Ghirardelli Square in San Francisco was the first festival marketplace project in the United States, opening in 1964.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Another notable example is the High Line in New York City, where a former elevated freight rail line was converted into a 1.45-mile-long public park.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Its adaptive reuse preserves industrial features while offering green space, public art, and city views.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Notable American museums adapted from defunct factories include the Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art (MassMOCA) in North Adams; the Watermill Center in Water Mill, New York; and The Dia Art Foundation Museum (Dia:Beacon) in Beacon, New York.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Throughout the United States until the 1970s, the vast majority of gas stations also offered mechanical work.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Converting the service bays into a convenience store in the 1980s and 1990s was common while still selling fuel.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Many others stopped selling fuel and became shops or offices.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Office-to-residential conversions are also common in the United States with office blocks in New York City, Washington, DC, and San Francisco slated for conversion to reduce the stock of vacant office blocks while addressing a housing shortage.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Adaptive reuse has been identified as a viable solution to the U.S. affordable housing crisis, particularly in urban areas.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] In Australia, there have been a number of adaptive reuse projects as the main cities have turned from industrial areas into areas of high value and business areas.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] In Sydney, sites such as the old Sydney Mint have been renovated and adapted into inner-city headquarters for the Historic Houses Trust of New South Wales.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] The movement of the city from an industrial, working class area into a gentrified area with high home prices has helped a number of adaptive reuse sites to exist within such an area.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] The old Hyde Park Barracks building has also been transformed from an old jail into a museum which documents and records the history of Australia's first settlers and convicts.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] The industrial history of Australia has also been an influencing factor in determining the types of buildings and areas which have gone on to become adaptive reuse sites, especially in the realms of private residences and community based buildings.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] The former Adelaide Stock Exchange building was purchased, restored and adapted to become the Science Exchange for the Royal Institution of Australia and the Australian Science Media Centre.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] In Europe, the main forms of adaptive reuse have been around former palaces and unused residences of the different European royal families into publicly accessible galleries and museums.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Many of the spaces have been restored with period finishes and display different collections of art, and design.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] In Paris, France, the most famous example of adaptive reuse is the Musée du Louvre, a former palace built in the late 12th century under Philip II and opened to the public as a museum in 1793.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Also, in London, England, the Queen's House, a former royal residence built around 1614, has become part of the National Maritime Museum and houses the museum's fine art collection.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] London is also home to many office-to-homes conversions following a March 2024 relaxation of planning rules to facilitate such conversions.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] As of January 2025, 121,000 flats were created in England under "permitted development rights" (PDR) which allows developers to convert commercial buildings without full planning consent and no affordable housing requirement.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] Other famous adaptive reuse sites in Europe include the Maastricht branch of the Selexyz chain in the Netherlands.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] This project received 2007 Lensvelt de Architect interior design award for its innovative reuse and is number one on *The Guardian'*s worldwide top ten bookstores list.
[src:apartment/adaptive-reuse] In Taichung, Dawn Cake bought the former ophthalmology hospital and converted it into a restaurant.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Named in honour of Adelaide of Saxe-Meiningen, wife of King William IV, the city was founded in 1836 as the planned capital for a freely settled British colony in Australia.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Colonel William Light, one of Adelaide's founding fathers, designed the city centre and chose its location close to the River Torrens.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Light's design, now listed as national heritage, set out the city centre in a grid layout known as "Light's Vision", interspaced by wide boulevards and large public squares, and entirely surrounded by park lands.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Colonial Adelaide was noted for its leading examples of religious freedom and progressive political reforms and became known as the "City of Churches" due to its diversity of faiths.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] It was Australia's third-most populous city until the postwar era.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Today, Adelaide is one of Australia's most visited travel destinations and hosts many festivals and sporting events, such as the Adelaide 500, Tour Down Under, Gather Round, LIV Golf Adelaide, and the Adelaide Fringe, the world's second largest annual arts festival.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Adelaide also hosts men's tennis with an ATP 250 event and women's tennis with a WTA 500 event, and will also become the new host of the Australian MotoGP Grand Prix from 2027.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The city has also been renowned for its automotive industry, having been the original host of the Australian Grand Prix in the FIA Formula One World Championship from 1985 to 1995.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Other features include its food and wine industries, its coastline and hills, its large defence and manufacturing operations, and its emerging space sector, including the Australian Space Agency being headquartered there.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] With one of the world's largest foreign-born populations, Adelaide has consistently ranked within the top-ten most liveable cities globally for much of the 21st century, being named in 2021 the most liveable city in the country and third in the world.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Its aesthetic appeal has also been recognised by *Architectural Digest*, which ranked Adelaide as the most beautiful city in the world in 2024.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] As South Australia's government and commercial centre, Adelaide is the site of many governmental and financial institutions.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Most of these are concentrated in the central business district along the cultural boulevards of North Terrace and King William Street.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Adelaide has also been classed as a Gamma + level global city as categorised by the Globalization and World Cities Research Network, with the city further linking economic regions to the worldwide economy.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is connected by extensive bus, train and tram networks, all of which are operated by Adelaide Metro, with its main railway terminus at the Adelaide railway station.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The city is also served by Adelaide Airport and Port Adelaide, both of which are among the busiest airports and seaports in Australia, respectively.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The amount of time Aboriginal people have been living in the area around modern-day Adelaide has been described as "millennia", "tens of thousands of years", "thousands of generations", or "innumerable generations".
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] At Hallett Cove Conservation Park in Adelaide's southern suburbs, archaeological evidence of Aboriginal culture has been found dating back 40,000 years.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The area was originally inhabited by the Kaurna people, one of many Aboriginal tribes in South Australia.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The city and parklands area also known as *Tarndanyangga* *Tandanya*, *Tarndanya* or *Tarntanya*.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The name means 'male red kangaroo rock', referring to a rock formation on the site that has now been destroyed.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The surrounding area was an open, grassy plain with patches of trees and shrubs, which had been managed by hundreds of generations.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Kaurna country encompassed the plains stretching north and south of Tarntanya, as well as the wooded foothills of the Mt Lofty Ranges.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The River Torrens was known as the Karrawirra Pari (Red Gum forest river).
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] About 300 Kaurna populated the Adelaide area, and were referred to by the settlers as the Cowandilla.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The more than 20 local clans across the plain lived seminomadic lives, with extensive mound settlements where huts were built repeatedly over centuries and a complex social structure, including a class of sorcerers separated from regular society.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Within a few decades of European settlement of South Australia, Kaurna culture was almost completely lost, with the last speaker of Kaurna language having died in 1929.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Extensive documentation by early missionaries and other researchers has enabled a modern revival of both, which has included a commitment by local and state governments to rename or include Kaurna names for many local places.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Based on the ideas of Edward Gibbon Wakefield about colonial reform, Robert Gouger petitioned the British government to create a new colony in Australia, resulting in the passage of the South Australia Act 1834.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Physical establishment of the colony began with the arrival of the first British colonisers in February 1836, followed by the commencement of colonial government in South Australia on 28 December 1836.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Proclaimed by the governor near The Old Gum Tree in what is now the suburb of Glenelg North, this day is annually commemorated in South Australia as Proclamation Day.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Named for Queen Adelaide, the site of the colony's capital was surveyed and laid out by Colonel William Light, the first surveyor-general of South Australia, with his own original, unique and topographically sensitive design.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was established as a planned colony of free settlers, promising civil liberties and freedom from religious persecution, based upon the ideas of Edward Gibbon Wakefield.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Wakefield had read accounts of Australian settlement while in prison in London for attempting to abduct an heiress, and realised that the eastern colonies suffered from a lack of available labour, due to the practice of giving land grants to all arrivals.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Wakefield's idea was for the Government to survey and sell the land at a rate that would maintain land values high enough to be unaffordable for labourers and journeymen.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Funds raised from the sale of land were to be used to bring out working-class emigrants, who would have to work hard for the monied settlers to ever afford their own land.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] As a result of this policy, Adelaide does not share the convict settlement history of other Australian cities like Sydney, Brisbane and Hobart.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] As it was believed that in a colony of free settlers there would be little crime, no provision was made for a gaol in Colonel Light's 1837 plan.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] But by mid-1837 the *South Australian Register* was warning of escaped convicts from New South Wales and tenders for a temporary gaol were sought.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Following a burglary, a murder, and two attempted murders in Adelaide during March 1838, Governor Hindmarsh created the South Australian Police Force (now the South Australia Police) in April 1838 under 21-year-old Henry Inman.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The first sheriff, Samuel Smart, was wounded during a robbery, and on 2 May 1838 one of the offenders, Michael Magee, became the first person to be hanged in South Australia.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] William Baker Ashton was appointed governor of the temporary gaol in 1839, and in 1840 George Strickland Kingston was commissioned to design Adelaide's new gaol.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Construction of Adelaide Gaol commenced in 1841.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's early history was marked by economic uncertainty and questionable leadership.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The first governor of South Australia, John Hindmarsh, clashed frequently with others, in particular the Resident Commissioner, James Hurtle Fisher.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The rural area surrounding Adelaide was surveyed by Light in preparation to sell a total of over 405 km2 (156 sq mi) of land.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's early economy started to get on its feet in 1838 with the arrival of livestock from Victoria, New South Wales and Tasmania.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Wool production provided an early basis for the South Australian economy.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] By 1860, wheat farms had been established from Encounter Bay in the south to Clare in the north.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] He was criticised for his response to the Maria massacre.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Gawler was recalled and replaced by George Edward Grey in 1841.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Grey slashed public expenditure against heavy opposition, although its impact was negligible at this point: silver was discovered in Glen Osmond that year, agriculture was well underway, and other mines sprung up all over the state, aiding Adelaide's commercial development.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The city exported meat, wool, wine, fruit and wheat by the time Grey left in 1845, contrasting with a low point in 1842 when one-third of Adelaide houses were abandoned.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Trade links with the rest of the Australian states were established after the Murray River was successfully navigated in 1853 by Francis Cadell, an Adelaide resident.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] South Australia became a self-governing colony in 1856 with the ratification of a new constitution by the British parliament.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Secret ballots were introduced, and a bicameral parliament was elected on 9 March 1857, by which time 109,917 people lived in the province.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] In 1860, the Thorndon Park reservoir was opened, providing an alternative water source to the now turbid River Torrens.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Gas street lighting was implemented in 1867, the University of Adelaide was founded in 1874, the South Australian Art Gallery opened in 1881 and the Happy Valley Reservoir opened in 1896.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] In the 1890s Australia was affected by a severe economic depression, ending a hectic era of land booms and tumultuous expansionism.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Financial institutions in Melbourne and banks in Sydney closed.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The national fertility rate fell and immigration was reduced to a trickle.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The value of South Australia's exports nearly halved.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Drought and poor harvests from 1884 compounded the problems, with some families leaving for Western Australia.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was not as badly hit as the larger gold-rush cities of Sydney and Melbourne, and silver and lead discoveries at Broken Hill provided some relief.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Only one year of deficit was recorded, but the price paid was retrenchments and lean public spending.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Wine and copper were the only industries not to suffer a downturn.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was Australia's third largest city for most of the 20th century.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Electric street lighting was introduced in 1900 and electric trams were transporting passengers in 1909.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] 28,000 men were sent to fight in World War I.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Crowley examined the reports of visitors in the early 20th century, noting that "many visitors to Adelaide admired the foresighted planning of its founders", as well as pondering the riches of the young city.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Adelaide enjoyed a postwar boom, entering a time of relative prosperity.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Its population grew, and it became the third most populous metropolitan area in the country, after Sydney and Melbourne.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Its prosperity was short-lived, with the return of droughts and the Great Depression of the 1930s.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] It later returned to fortune under strong government leadership.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Secondary industries helped reduce the state's dependence on primary industries.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] World War II brought industrial stimulus and diversification to Adelaide under the Playford Government, which advocated Adelaide as a safe place for manufacturing due to its less vulnerable location.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Shipbuilding was expanded at the nearby port of Whyalla.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The South Australian Government in this period built on former wartime manufacturing industries but neglected cultural facilities which meant South Australia's economy lagged behind.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] International manufacturers like Holden and Chrysler made use of these factories around the Adelaide area in suburbs like Elizabeth, completing its transformation from an agricultural service centre to a 20th-century motor city.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The Mannum–Adelaide pipeline brought River Murray water to Adelaide in 1955 and an airport opened at West Beach in 1955.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Flinders University and the Flinders Medical Centre were established in the 1960s at Bedford Park, south of the city.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Today, Flinders Medical Centre is one of the largest teaching hospitals in South Australia.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] In the post-war years around the early 1960s, Adelaide was surpassed by Brisbane as Australia's third largest city.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The Dunstan Governments of the 1970s saw something of an Adelaide "cultural revival", establishing a wide array of social reforms.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The city became noted for its progressivism as South Australia became the first Australian state or territory to decriminalise homosexuality between consenting adults in 1975.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Adelaide became a centre for the arts, building upon the biennial "Adelaide Festival of Arts" that commenced in 1960.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The State Bank collapsed in 1991 during an economic recession.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The effects lasted until 2004, when Standard & Poor's reinstated South Australia's AAA credit rating.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's tallest building, completed in 2020, is called the Adelaidean and is located at 11 Frome Street.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] In the early years of the 21st century, a significant increase in the state government's spending on Adelaide's infrastructure occurred.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The Rann government invested A$535 million in a major upgrade of the Adelaide Oval to enable Australian Football League to be played in the city centre and more than A$2 billion to build a new Royal Adelaide Hospital on land adjacent to the Adelaide Railway Station.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The Glenelg tramline was extended through the city to Hindmarsh down to East Terrace and the suburban railway line extended south to Seaford.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Following a period of stagnation in the 1990s and 2000s, Adelaide began several major developments and redevelopments.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide Convention Centre was redeveloped and expanded at a cost of A$350 million beginning in 2012.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The government invested more than A$2 billion to build a desalination plant, powered by renewable energy, as an "insurance policy" against droughts affecting Adelaide's water supply.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide Festival, Fringe, and Womadelaide became annual events.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is north of the Fleurieu Peninsula, on the Adelaide Plains between the Gulf St Vincent and the relatively low-lying Mount Lofty Ranges (Mount Lofty, the highest point, is 710 metres above sea level).
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The city stretches 20 km (12 mi) from the coast to the foothills, and 90 km (56 mi) from Gawler at its northern extent to Sellicks Beach in the south.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The city sits at an average elevation of 50 metres (160 ft) above sea level.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Mount Lofty, east of the Adelaide metropolitan region in the Adelaide Hills at an elevation of 727 metres (2,385 ft), is the tallest point of the city and in the state south of Burra.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The city borders the Temperate Grassland of South Australia in the east, an endangered vegetation community.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Much of Adelaide was bushland before British settlement, with some variation – sandhills, swamps and marshlands were prevalent around the coast.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The loss of the sandhills to urban development had a particularly destructive effect on the coastline due to erosion.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Where practical, the government has implemented programs to rebuild and vegetate sandhills at several of Adelaide's beachside suburbs.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Tennyson Dunes is the largest contiguous, tertiary dune system contained entirely within Metropolitan Adelaide, providing refuge for a variety of remnant species formerly found along the entire coastline.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Much of the original vegetation has been cleared with what is left to be found in reserves such as the Cleland National Park and Belair National Park.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] A number of creeks and rivers flow through the Adelaide region.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The largest are the Torrens and Onkaparinga catchments.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Adelaide relies on its many reservoirs for water supply with the Happy Valley Reservoir supplying around 40% and the much larger Mount Bold Reservoir 10% of Adelaide's domestic requirements respectively.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Adelaide and its surrounding area is one of the most seismically active regions in Australia.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] On 1 March 1954 at 3:40 am Adelaide experienced its largest recorded earthquake to date, with the epicentre 12 km from the city centre at Darlington, and a reported magnitude of 5.6.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Most of the Adelaide metropolitan area lies in the downthrown St Vincent Basin and its embayments, including the Adelaide Plains Sub-basin, and the Golden Grove, Noarlunga and Willunga Embayments.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] These basins contain deposits of Tertiary marine and non-marine sands and limestones, which form important aquifers.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is a planned city, designed by the first Surveyor-General of South Australia, Colonel William Light.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] His plan, sometimes referred to as "Light's Vision" (also the name of a statue of him on Montefiore Hill), arranged Adelaide in a grid, with five squares in the Adelaide city centre and a ring of parks, known as the Adelaide Parklands, surrounding it.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Light's selection of the location for the city was initially unpopular with the early settlers, as well as South Australia's first governor, John Hindmarsh, due to its distance from the harbour at Port Adelaide, and the lack of fresh water there.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Light successfully persisted with his choice of location against this initial opposition.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The benefits of Light's design are numerous: Adelaide has had wide multi-lane roads from its beginning, an easily navigable cardinal direction grid layout and an expansive green ring around the city centre.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] There are two sets of ring roads in Adelaide that have resulted from the original design.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The inner ring route (A21) borders the parklands, and the outer route (A3/A13/A16/A17) completely bypasses the inner city via (in clockwise order) Grand Junction Road, Hampstead Road, Ascot Avenue, Portrush Road, Cross Road and South Road.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Suburban expansion has to some extent outgrown Light's original plan.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Numerous former outlying villages and "country towns", as well as the satellite city of Elizabeth, have been enveloped by its suburban sprawl.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Expanding developments in the Adelaide Hills region led to the construction of the South Eastern Freeway to cope with growth, which has subsequently led to new developments and further improvements to that transport corridor.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Similarly, the booming development in Adelaide's South led to the construction of the Southern Expressway.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] New roads are not the only transport infrastructure developed to cope with the urban growth.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The O-Bahn Busway and Adelaide Metro are examples of a unique solution to Tea Tree Gully's transport woes in the 1980s.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The development of the nearby suburb of Golden Grove in the late 1980s followed a planned approach to urban growth.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] In the 1960s, a Metropolitan Adelaide Transport Study Plan was proposed to cater for the future growth of the city.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The plan involved the construction of freeways, expressways and the upgrade of certain aspects of the public transport system.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The then premier Steele Hall approved many parts of the plan and the government went as far as purchasing land for the project.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The later Labor government elected under Don Dunstan shelved the plan, but allowed the purchased land to remain vacant, should the future need for freeways arise.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] In 1980, the Liberal party won government and premier David Tonkin committed his government to selling off the land acquired for the MATS plan, ensuring that even when needs changed, the construction of most MATS-proposed freeways would be impractical.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Some parts of this land have been used for transport, (e.g. the O-Bahn Busway and Southern Expressway), while most has been progressively subdivided for residential use.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] In 2008, the SA Government announced plans for a network of transport-oriented developments across the Adelaide metropolitan area and purchased a 10 hectare industrial site at Bowden for $52.5 million as the first of these developments.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Historically, Adelaide's suburban residential areas have been characterised by single-storey detached houses built on 1,000-square-metre (1⁄4-acre) blocks.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] A relative lack of suitable, locally available timber for construction purposes led to the early development of a brick-making industry, as well as the use of stone, for houses and other buildings.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] By 1891, 68% of houses were built of stone, 15% of timber, and 10% of brick, with brick also being widely used in stone houses for quoins, door and window surrounds, and chimneys and fireplaces.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] There is a wide variety in the styles of these houses.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Until the 1960s, most of the more substantial houses were built of red brick, though many front walls were of ornamental stone.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Then cream bricks became fashionable, and in the 1970s, deep red and brown bricks became popular.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Until the 1970s, roofs tended to be clad with (painted) corrugated iron or cement or clay tiles, usually red "terracotta".
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Since then, Colorbond corrugated steel has dominated.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Up to the 1970s, most houses were of "double brick" construction on concrete footings, with timber floors laid on joists supported by "dwarf walls".
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The use of precast concrete panels for floor and wall construction has also increased.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] In addition to this, a significant factor in Adelaide's suburban history is the role of the South Australian Housing Trust.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Adelaide has a hot-summer Mediterranean climate (*Csa*) under the Köppen climate classification.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The city has hot, dry summers and cool winters with moderate rainfall.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Most rain falls in the winter months, leading to the suggestion that the climate be classified as a "cold monsoon".
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Rainfall is unreliable, light and infrequent throughout summer, although heavy falls can occur.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The winter has fairly reliable rainfall with June being the wettest month of the year, averaging around 80 mm.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Frosts are occasional, with the most notable occurrences in 1908 and 1982.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is a windy city with significant wind chill in winter, which makes the temperature seem colder than it actually is.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Snowfall in the metropolitan area is extremely rare, although light and sporadic falls in the nearby hills and at Mount Lofty occur during winter.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Dewpoints in the summer typically range from 8 to 10 °C (46 to 50 °F).
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] There are usually several days in summer where the temperature reaches 40.0 °C (104.0 °F) or above.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] While conditions vary from year-to-year, a warming trend has been increasing in recent years, and with drought conditions experienced in SA in 2024−25, Adelaide has had to rely on desalination to augment its water supply.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The city features 90.6 clear days annually.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The average sea temperature ranges from 13.7 °C (56.7 °F) in August to 21.2 °C (70.2 °F) in February.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was consistently ranked in the world's 10 most liveable cities through the 2010s by The Economist Intelligence Unit.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] In June 2021, *The Economist* ranked Adelaide the third most liveable city in the world, behind Auckland and Osaka.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] In June 2023, Adelaide was ranked the twelfth most liveable city in the world by the Economist Intelligence Unit.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] In December 2021, Adelaide was named the world's second National Park City, after the state government had lobbied for this title.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] It was ranked the most liveable city in Australia by the Property Council of Australia, based on surveys of residents' views of their own city, between 2010 and 2013, dropping to second place in 2014.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Adelaide, as the capital of South Australia, is the seat of the Government of South Australia.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The bicameral Parliament of South Australia consists of the lower house known as the House of Assembly and the upper house known as the Legislative Council.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] General elections are held every four years, the last being the 2022 South Australian state election.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] As Adelaide is South Australia's capital and most populous city, the State Government co-operates extensively with the City of Adelaide.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] In 2006, the Ministry for the City of Adelaide was created to facilitate the State Government's collaboration with the Adelaide City Council and the Lord Mayor to improve Adelaide's image.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The State Parliament's Capital City Committee is also involved in the governance of the City of Adelaide, being primarily concerned with the planning of Adelaide's urban development and growth.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Reflecting South Australia's status as Australia's most centralised state, Adelaide elects a substantial majority of the South Australian House of Assembly.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Of the 47 seats in the chamber, 34 seats (three-quarters of the legislature) are based in Adelaide, and two rural seats include Adelaide suburbs.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide metropolitan area is divided between nineteen local government areas.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] At its centre, the City of Adelaide administers the Adelaide city centre, North Adelaide, and the surrounding Adelaide Parklands.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] It is the oldest municipal authority in Australia and was established in 1840, when Adelaide and Australia's first mayor, James Hurtle Fisher, was elected.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] From 1919 onwards, the city has had a Lord Mayor, the current being Lord Mayor *The Right Honourable* Jane Lomax-Smith.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's inhabitants are known as Adelaideans.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Compared with Australia's other state capitals, Adelaide is growing at a rate similar to Sydney and Hobart (see List of cities in Australia by population).
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] In 2024, it had a metropolitan population (including suburbs) of 1,469,163, making it Australia's fifth-largest city.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] 77% of the population of South Australia are residents of the Adelaide metropolitan area, making South Australia one of the most centralised states.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Major areas of population growth in recent years have been in outer suburbs such as Mawson Lakes and Golden Grove.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's inhabitants occupy 366,912 houses, 57,695 semi-detached, row terrace or town houses and 49,413 flats, units or apartments.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] About one sixth (17.1%) of the population had university qualifications.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The number of Adelaideans with vocational qualifications (such as tradespersons) fell from 62.1% of the labour force in the 1991 census to 52.4% in the 2001 census.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is aging more rapidly than other Australian capital cities.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] More than a quarter (27.5%) of Adelaide's population is aged 55 years or older, in comparison to the national average of 25.6%.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Adelaide has the lowest number of children (under-15-year-olds), who comprised 17.7% of the population, compared to the national average of 19.3%.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Overseas-born Adelaideans composed 31.3% of the total population at the 2021 census.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The five largest groups of overseas-born were from England (5.7%), India (3.1%), Mainland China (1.8%), Vietnam (1.2%) and Italy (1.1%).
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Suburbs including Newton, Payneham and Campbelltown in the east and Torrensville, West Lakes and Fulham to the west, have large Greek and Italian communities.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The Italian consulate is located in the western suburb of Hindmarsh.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Large Vietnamese populations are settled in the north-western suburbs of Woodville, Kilkenny, Pennington, Mansfield Park and Athol Park and also Parafield Gardens and Pooraka in Adelaide's north.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Migrants from India and Sri Lanka have settled into inner suburban areas of Adelaide including the inner northern suburbs of Blair Athol, Kilburn and Enfield and the inner southern suburbs of Plympton, Park Holme and Kurralta Park.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Suburbs such as Para Hills, Salisbury, Ingle Farm and Blair Athol in the north and Findon, West Croydon and Seaton and other Western suburbs have sizeable Afghan communities.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Chinese migrants favour settling in the eastern and north eastern suburbs including Kensington Gardens, Greenacres, Modbury and Golden Grove.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Mawson Lakes has a large international student population, due to its proximity to the University of South Australia campus.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] At the 2021 census, 1.7% of Adelaide's population identified as being Indigenous — Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islanders.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] At the 2016 census, 75.4% of the population spoke English at home.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The other languages most commonly spoken at home were Italian (2.1%), Standard Mandarin (2.1%), Greek (1.7%) Vietnamese (1.4%), and Cantonese (0.7%).
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The Kaurna language, spoken by the area's original inhabitants, had no living speakers in the middle of the 20th century, but since the 1990s there has been a sustained revival effort from academics and Kaurna elders.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was founded on a vision of religious tolerance that attracted a wide variety of religious practitioners.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] This led to it being known as *The City of Churches*.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] But approximately 28% of the population expressed no religious affiliation in the 2011 Census, compared with the national average of 22.3%, making Adelaide one of Australia's least religious cities.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] According to 2021 census, 39.8% of the population of Adelaide identify as Christian, with the largest denominations being Catholic (16.4%), Anglican (7.0%), Uniting Church (3.9%) and Greek Orthodox (2.4%).
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Non-Christian faith communities, representing 9.5% from Adelaide's population, include Islam (2.8%), Hinduism (2.7%) and Buddhism (2.3%).
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The Jewish community of the city dates back to 1840.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Eight years later, 58 Jews lived in the city.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] A synagogue was built in 1871, when 435 Jews lived in the city.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Many took part in the city councils, such as Judah Moss Solomon (1852–66).
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Three Jews have been elected to the position of city mayor.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] In 1968, the Jewish population of Adelaide numbered about 1,200; in 2001, according to the Australian census, 979 persons declared themselves to be Jewish by religion.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] In 2011, over 1,000 Jews were living in the city, served by an Orthodox synagogue, Adelaide Hebrew Congregation and a Reform synagogue, **Beit Shalom**, in addition to a virtual Jewish museum.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Massada College, a Jewish day school opened in the city in 1976 and closed in 2011.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide Holocaust Museum and Andrew Steiner Education Centre opened in 2020.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The "Afghan" community in Australia first became established in the 1860s when camels and their Pathan, Punjabi, Baluchi and Sindhi handlers began to be used to open up settlement in the continent's arid interior.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Until eventually superseded by the advent of the railways and motor vehicles, camels played an invaluable economic and social role in transporting heavy loads of goods to and from isolated settlements and mines.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] This is acknowledged by the name of The Ghan, the passenger train operating between Adelaide, Alice Springs, and Darwin.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The Central Adelaide Mosque is regarded as Australia's oldest permanent mosque; an earlier mosque at Marree in northern South Australia, dating from 1861 to 1862 and subsequently abandoned or demolished, has now been rebuilt.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] South Australia's largest employment sectors are health care and social assistance, surpassing manufacturing in SA as the largest employer since 2006–07.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] In 2009–10, manufacturing in SA had average annual employment of 83,700 persons compared with 103,300 for health care and social assistance.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Health care and social assistance represented nearly 13% of the state average annual employment.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide Hills wine region is an iconic and viable economic region for both the state and country in terms of wine production and sale.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The retail trade is the second largest employer in SA (2009–10), with over 91,900 jobs, and 12 per cent of the state workforce.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Manufacturing, defence technology, high-tech electronic systems and research, commodity export and corresponding service industries all play a role in the SA economy.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Almost half of all cars produced in Australia were made in Adelaide at the Holden Elizabeth Plant in Elizabeth.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The site ceased operating in November 2017.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The collapse of the State Bank in 1992 resulted in large levels of state public debt (as much as A$4 billion).
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The collapse meant that successive governments enacted lean budgets, cutting spending, which was a setback to the further economic development of the city and state.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] As of January 2026, the government has an AA+ credit rating.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The global media conglomerate News Corporation was founded in, and until 2004 incorporated in, Adelaide, and the city is still considered the Corporation's "spiritual" home by its founder, Rupert Murdoch.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Australia's largest oil company, Santos, prominent South Australian brewery, Coopers, and national retailer Harris Scarfe also call Adelaide their home.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] In 2018, at which time more than 80 organisations employed 800 people in the space sector in South Australia, Adelaide was chosen for the headquarters of a new Australian Space Agency.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] It is working to triple the size of the Australian space industry and create 20,000 new jobs by 2030.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is home to a large proportion of Australia's defence industries, which contribute over A$1 billion to South Australia's Gross State Product.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Others, such as Saab Systems and Raytheon, are in or near Technology Park.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] ASC Pty Ltd, is based in the industrial suburb of Osborne and is also a part of Technology Park.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] South Australia was charged with constructing Australia's *Collins*-class submarines and more recently the A$6 billion contract to construct the Royal Australian Navy's new air-warfare destroyers.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] As of November 2015, Greater Adelaide had an unemployment rate of 7.4% with a youth unemployment rate of 15%.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The median weekly individual income for people aged 15 years and over was $447 per week in 2006, compared with $466 nationally.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The median family income was $1,137 per week, compared with $1,171 nationally.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's housing and living costs are substantially lower than that of other Australian cities, with housing being notably cheaper.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The median Adelaide house price is half that of Sydney and two-thirds that of Melbourne.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The three-month trend unemployment rate to March 2007 was 6.2%.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] The Northern suburbs' unemployment rate is disproportionately higher than the other regions of Adelaide at 8.3%, while the East and South are lower than the Adelaide average at 4.9% and 5.0% respectively.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Over the decade March 2001 – March 2010, Metropolitan Adelaide median house prices approximately tripled.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] 11%p.a. compounding) In the five years March 2007 – March 2012, prices increased by approx.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] March 2012 – March 2017 saw a further increase of 19% – approx.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] no longer release a median house price for the Adelaide Metropolitan area, so figures retrieved are from Dept of the Premier and Cabinet.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Each quarter, The Alternative and Direct Investment Securities Association (ADISA) publishes a list of median house sale prices by suburb and Local Government Area.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p01] Quarterly Reports for the last two years can be found on the REISA website.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Education forms an increasingly important part of the city's economy, with the South Australian Government and educational institutions attempting to position Adelaide as "Australia's education hub" and marketing it as a "Learning City".
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The number of international students studying in Adelaide has increased rapidly in recent years to 30,726 in 2015, of which 1,824 were secondary school students.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is the birthplace of three Nobel laureates, more than any other Australian city: physicist William Lawrence Bragg and pathologists Howard Florey and Robin Warren, all of whom completed secondary and tertiary education at St Peter's College and the University of Adelaide.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is also the hometown of mathematician Terence Tao.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] There are two systems of primary and secondary schools, a public system operated by the South Australian Government's Department for Education, and a private system of independent and Catholic schools.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] South Australian schools provide education under the Australian Curriculum for reception to Year 10 students.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] In Years 10 to 12, students study for the South Australian Certificate of Education (SACE).
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] They have the option of incorporating vocational education and training (VET) courses or a flexible learning option (FLO).
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] South Australia also has 24 schools that use International Baccalaureate programs as an alternative to the Australian Curriculum or SACE.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] These programs include the IB Primary Years Programme, the IB Middle Years Programme, and the IB Diploma Programme.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] For South Australian students who cannot attend a traditional school, including students who live in rural or remote areas, the state government runs the Open Access College (OAC), which provides virtual teaching.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The OAC has a campus in Marden which caters to students from reception to Year 12 and adults who haven't been able to complete their SACE.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Guardians are also able to apply for their child to be educated from home as long as they provide an education program which meets the same requirements as the Australian Curriculum as well as opportunities for social interaction.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] There are two public universities local to Adelaide, as well as one private university and three constituent colleges of foreign universities.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Flinders University of South Australia, Adelaide University and Torrens University Australia—part of the Laureate International Universities are based in Adelaide.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The University of Adelaide was ranked in the top 150 universities worldwide.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Flinders ranked in the top 250 and Uni SA in the top 300.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Torrens University Australia is part of an international network of over 70 higher education institutions in more than 30 countries worldwide.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Adelaide University is a recent amalgamation between the University of Adelaide and the University of South Australia, ranked in the top 150 globally and top 10 nationally.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Today, it stands as Australia's third-oldest university and a member of the leading "Group of Eight".
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The merged university has over 64,000 students and two main campuses on North Terrace, with many other campuses across South Australia, including in Whyalla and Mount Gambier.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The two universities had multiple proposals to merge into a single university.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] A proposal in 2018 failed due to uncertainty as to the new name and leadership of the merged university.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] In 2022, the universities announced a new merger proposal, with the name and leadership issues settled and support from the South Australian government.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Flinders University, with 25,184 students, is based in the southern suburb of Bedford Park, alongside the Flinders Medical Centre, with additional campuses in neighbouring Tonsley and in Victoria Square in the city centre.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] In 2024, the University of the Sunshine Coast opened a new campus in Adelaide where undergraduate and master's courses in ICT and business are offered.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide College of Divinity is at Brooklyn Park.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] There are several South Australian TAFE (Technical and Further Education) campuses in the metropolitan area that provide a range of vocational education and training.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide College of the Arts, as a school of TAFE SA, provides nationally recognised training in visual and performing arts.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The Workers' Educational Association of South Australia (WEA-SA) is an independent not-for-profit adult education organisation based in Adelaide.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Established in 1913, it is one of Australia's longest running providers of community-based adult learning.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] WEA-SA delivers short courses, lectures, cultural programs, travel and interest clubs designed to promote lifelong learning.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] StudyAdelaide, a collaboration between the South Australian government and the tertiary education sector, maintains an on-line list of schools, universities, and higher education institutions in SA.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] In addition to the universities, Adelaide is home to research institutes, including the Royal Institution of Australia, established in 2009 as a counterpart to the two-hundred-year-old Royal Institution of Great Britain.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] While established as a British province, and very much English in terms of its culture, Adelaide attracted immigrants from other parts of Europe early on, including German and other European non-conformists escaping religious persecution.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The first German Lutherans arrived in 1838, bringing with them the vine cuttings that they used to found the acclaimed wineries of the Barossa Valley.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The Royal Adelaide Show is an annual agricultural show and state fair, established in 1839 and now a huge event held in the Adelaide Showground annually.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's arts scene flourished in the 1960s and 1970s with the support of successive premiers from both major political parties.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The renowned Adelaide Festival of Arts was established in 1960 under Thomas Playford, which in the same year spawned an unofficial uncurated series of performances and exhibits which grew into the Adelaide Fringe.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Construction of the Adelaide Festival Centre began under Steele Hall in 1970 and was completed under the subsequent government of Don Dunstan, who also established the South Australian Film Corporation in 1972 and the State Opera of South Australia in 1976.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] With the Festival, the Fringe, WOMADelaide, Writers' Week and the Adelaide 500 street motor racing event (along with evening music concerts) all happening in early March, the period became known colloquially as "Mad March".
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] In 2014, Ghil'ad Zuckermann founded the Adelaide Language Festival.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] There are many international cultural fairs, most notably the German Schützenfest and Greek Glendi.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Adelaide holds an annual Christmas pageant, the world's largest Christmas parade.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] As the state capital, Adelaide has a great number of cultural institutions, many of them along the boulevard of North Terrace.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The Art Gallery of South Australia, with about 35,000 works, holds Australia's second largest state-based collection.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Adjacent are the South Australian Museum and State Library of South Australia.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide Botanic Garden, National Wine Centre and Tandanya National Aboriginal Cultural Institute are nearby in the East End of the city.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] In the back of the State Library lies the Migration Museum, Australia's oldest museum of its kind.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Further west, the Lion Arts Centre is home to ACE Open, which showcases contemporary art; Dance Hub SA; and other studios and arts industry spaces.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The Mercury Cinema and the JamFactory ceramics and design gallery are just around the corner.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide Festival Centre (which includes the Dunstan Playhouse, Festival Theatre and Space Theatre), on the banks of the Torrens, is the focal point for much of the cultural activity in the city and home to the State Theatre Company of South Australia.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Other live music and theatre venues include the Adelaide Entertainment Centre; Adelaide Oval; Memorial Drive Park; Thebarton Theatre; Adelaide Town Hall; Her Majesty's Theatre; Queen's Theatre; Holden Street Theatres; and the Hopgood Theatre.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The Lion Arts Factory, within the Lion Arts Centre, hosts contemporary music in a wide range of genres, as does "The Gov" in Hindmarsh.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The city also has numerous smaller theatres, pubs and cabaret bars which host performances.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] In 2015, it was said that there were now more live music venues per capita in Adelaide than any other capital city in the southern hemisphere, *Lonely Planet* labelled Adelaide "Australia's live music city", and the city was recognised as a "City of Music" by the UNESCO Creative Cities Network.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Although there were many pubs hosting live music in the CBD in past, the number has slowly diminished.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The Grace Emily on Waymouth Street, which was refurbished as a live music venue around 2000, is popular with musicians and patrons alike.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The Crown & Anchor ("the Cranker") was saved from demolition in 2024 after a vigorous campaign by the public as well as many musicians and politicians.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] New legislation passed on 11 September 2024 designates the entire Adelaide CBD as a "live music venue area", and gives protection to selected live music venues.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] In addition to its own WOMAD (WOMADelaide), Adelaide has attracted several touring music festivals, including Creamfields, Laneway, and Groovin' (some since defunct).
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Adelaide has produced musical groups and individuals who have achieved national and international fame.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Noted rocker Jimmy Barnes (formerly lead vocalist with Cold Chisel) spent most of his youth in the northern suburb of Elizabeth.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Australian singer-songwriter Paul Kelly grew up in Adelaide and was head prefect at Rostrevor College.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The first *Australian Idol* winner, Guy Sebastian, hails from the north-eastern suburb of Golden Grove.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] All of the five Australian national television networks broadcast both high-definition digital and standard-definition digital television services in Adelaide.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] They share three transmission towers on the ridge near the summit of Mount Lofty.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] There are two other transmission sites at 25 Grenfell Street, Adelaide and Elizabeth Downs.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The two government-funded stations are run by the Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC South Australia) and the Special Broadcasting Service (SBS).
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The Seven Network and Network Ten both own their Adelaide stations (SAS-7 and ADS-10 respectively).
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's NWS-9 is part of the Nine Network.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Adelaide also has a community television station, Channel 44.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] As part of a nationwide phase-out of analogue television in Australia, Adelaide's analogue television service was shut down on 2 April 2013.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] There are 20 radio stations that serve the metropolitan area, as well as four stations that serve only parts of the metropolitan area; six commercial stations, six community stations, six national stations and two narrowcast stations.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] DAB+ digital radio has been broadcasting in metropolitan Adelaide since 20 May 2009, and currently offers a choice of 41 stations all operated by the existing licensed radio broadcasters, which includes high-quality simulcast of all AM and FM stations.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The main sports played professionally in Adelaide are Australian Rules football, soccer, cricket, netball, and basketball.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is the home of two Australian Football League teams: the Adelaide Football Club and Port Adelaide Football Club, and one A-League soccer team, Adelaide United.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] A local Australian rules football league, the South Australian National Football League (SANFL), is made up of 10 teams from around Adelaide.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The SANFL has been in operation since 1877 when it began as the South Australian Football Association (SAFA) before changing its name to the SANFL in 1927.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The SANFL is the oldest surviving football league of any code played in Australia.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Since completion of the upgrade, home games for Adelaide Crows and Port Adelaide now take place at Adelaide Oval.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Since 1884, Adelaide Oval has also hosted an international cricket test every summer, along with a number of One Day International cricket matches.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Memorial Drive Park, adjacent to the Adelaide Oval, used to host Davis Cup and other major tennis events, including the Australian Open and the Adelaide International.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's professional association football team, Adelaide United, play in the A-League.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Founded in 2003, their home ground is Coopers Stadium, which has a capacity of 16,500 and is one of the few purpose-built soccer stadia in Australia.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Prior to United's foundation, Adelaide City and West Adelaide represented the city in the National Soccer League.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The two sides, which contest the Adelaide derby against one another, now play in the National Premier Leagues South Australia.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] For two years, 1997 and 1998, Adelaide was represented in Australia's top level rugby league, after the New South Wales Rugby League had played a single game per season at the Adelaide Oval for five years starting in 1991.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide Rams were formed and played in the breakaway Super League (SL) competition in 1997 before moving to the new National Rugby League in 1998.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Initially playing at the Adelaide Oval, the club moved to the more suitable Hindmarsh Stadium late in the 1998 season.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] As part of a peace deal with the Australian Rugby League to end the Super League war, the club's owners News Limited (who were also owners of the SL) suddenly closed the club only weeks before the start of the 1999 season.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Adelaide has two professional basketball teams, the men's team being the Adelaide 36ers which plays in the National Basketball League (NBL) and the women's team, the Adelaide Lightning which plays in the Women's National Basketball League (WNBL).
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide 36ers play at the Adelaide Entertainment Centre while the Adelaide Lightning play at the Adelaide Arena (Previously Titanium Security Arena).
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Adelaide has a professional netball team, the Adelaide Thunderbirds, which plays in the national netball competition, the Super Netball championship, with home games played at Netball SA Stadium.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The Thunderbirds occasionally play games or finals at the Titanium Security Arena, while international netball matches are usually played at the 10,500 seat Adelaide Entertainment Centre.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The Titanium Security Arena has a capacity of 8,000 and is the largest purpose-built basketball stadium in Australia.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Since 1999 Adelaide and its surrounding areas have hosted the Tour Down Under bicycle race, organised and directed by Adelaide-based Michael Turtur.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Turtur won an Olympic gold medal for Australia in the 4000 m team pursuit at the 1984 Los Angeles Olympics.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The Tour Down Under is the largest cycling event outside Europe and was the first event outside Europe to be granted UCI ProTour status.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The 2024 Women's Tour Down Under cycle stage race was held in and around Adelaide, South Australia from 12 to 14 January 2024.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Adelaide maintains a franchise in the Australian Baseball League, the Adelaide Giants.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] They have been playing since 2009, and their home stadium (until 2016) was Norwood Oval.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] From 2016 the team moved to the Diamond Sports Stadium located near the Adelaide International Airport due to renovations at Norwood.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Adelaide also has an ice hockey team, Adelaide Adrenaline in the Australian Ice Hockey League (AIHL).
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] It was national champions in 2009 and plays its games at the IceArenA.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The Australian Grand Prix for World Championship Formula One racing was hosted by Adelaide from 1985 to 1995 on the Adelaide Street Circuit which was laid out in the city's East End as well as the eastern parklands including the Victoria Park Racecourse.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The Grand Prix became a source of pride, and losing the event to Melbourne in a surprise announcement in mid-1993 left a void that has since been filled with the Adelaide 500 for V8 Supercar racing, held on a modified version of the same street circuit.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The Classic Adelaide, a rally of classic sporting vehicles, is also held in the city and its surrounds.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Adelaide formerly had three horse racing venues.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Victoria Park, Cheltenham Park Racecourse, both of which have now closed, and Morphettville Racecourse that remains the home of the South Australian Jockey Club.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] It also has Globe Derby Park for Harness racing that opened in 1969, and by 1973 had become Adelaide's premier harness racing venue taking over from the Wayville Showgrounds, as well as Greyhound Park for greyhound racing that opened in 1972.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The World Solar Challenge race attracts teams from around the world, most of which are fielded by universities or corporations, although some are fielded by high schools.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The race has a 20-years' history spanning nine races, with the inaugural event taking place in 1987.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Adelaide hosted the 2012 World Bowls Championships at Lockleys Bowling Club, becoming the third city in the world to have held the championships twice, having previously hosted the event in 1996.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Dirt track speedway is also popular in Adelaide with three operating speedways.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Adelaide Motorsport Park, located adjacent to the Adelaide International Raceway road racing circuit at Virginia (24 km (15 mi) north of the city centre) has been in continuous operation since 1979 after the closure of the popular Rowley Park Speedway.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Gillman Speedway located in the semi-industrial suburb of Gillman, has been in operation since 1998 and caters to Motorcycle speedway and Sidecars, while the Sidewinders Speedway located in Wingfield is also a motorcycle speedway dedicated to Under-16 riders and has been in operation since 1978.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] In 2016, backed by South Australia's Peregrine Corporation opened up a multi-purpose facility; a state-of-the-art motorsporting park and a hotel alongside its newer OTR service station outside a small township of Tailem Bend currently named The Bend Motorsport Park.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Design for thrill seekers and rev-heads the facility currently host South Australia's second Supercars motoring event during a round in August.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is home to the Great Southern Slam, the world's largest roller derby tournament.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The tournament has been held biennially over Australia's Queen's Birthday holiday weekend since 2010.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] In 2014, and 2016 the tournament featured 45 teams playing in two divisions.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] In 2018, the tournament has expanded to 48 teams competing in three divisions.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Being centrally located on the Australian mainland, Adelaide forms a strategic transport hub for east–west and north–south routes.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The city itself has a metropolitan public transport system managed by and known as the Adelaide Metro.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Tramways were largely dismantled in the 1950s, but saw a revival in the 2010s with upgrades and extensions.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Road transport in Adelaide has historically been easier than many of the other Australian cities, with a well-defined city layout and wide multiple-lane roads from the beginning of its development.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Adelaide was known as a "twenty-minute city", with commuters having been able to travel from metropolitan outskirts to the city proper in roughly twenty minutes.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] However, such arterial roads often experience traffic congestion as the city grows.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide metropolitan area has one freeway and four expressways.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide metropolitan area has two commercial airports, Adelaide Airport and Parafield Airport.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Adelaide Airport, in Adelaide's south-western suburbs, serves almost 9 million passengers annually, with an extensive number of direct flight routes within Australia, as well as other destinations in Oceania, Asia and North America.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Parafield Airport, Adelaide's second airport 18 kilometres (11 miles) north of the city centre, is used for small aircraft, pilot training and recreational aviation purposes.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Parafield Airport served as Adelaide's main aerodrome until the opening of the Adelaide Airport in February 1955.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is also home to a military airport, known as RAAF Base Edinburgh, located in the northern suburbs.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] It was built in 1955 in a joint initiative with the United Kingdom for weapon development.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's two largest hospitals are the Royal Adelaide Hospital (RAH) in Adelaide Parklands, a teaching hospital affiliated with the University of Adelaide (800 beds), and the Flinders Medical Centre (580 beds) at Bedford Park, affiliated with Flinders University.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The RAH also operates additional campuses for specialist care throughout the suburbs including the Hampstead Rehabilitation Centre (150 beds) at Northfield and the Glenside Campus (129 beds) for acute mental health services.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Other major public hospitals are the Women's and Children's Hospital (305 beds), at North Adelaide; the Queen Elizabeth Hospital (340 beds) at Woodville; Modbury Hospital (174 beds) at Modbury; and the Lyell McEwin Hospital (198 beds) at Elizabeth Vale.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Numerous private hospitals are also located throughout the city, with the largest operators being not-for-profits Adelaide Community Healthcare Alliance (three hospitals) and Calvary Care (four hospitals).
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] In 2017, the RAH was relocated from the city's East End to a new AU$2.3 billion facility built over former railyards in the West End.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] SAHMRI, with additional external funding, has built a $300 million second facility completed in 2024, which was intended to house the Australian Bragg Centre with Australia's first proton therapy unit.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Construction is underway for the Women's and Children's Hospital to be relocated to the precinct adjacent the RAH by 2030.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The largest provider of community health care within Adelaide is the not-for-profit Royal District Nursing Service, which provides out of hospital care and hospital avoidance care.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's energy requirements were originally met by the Adelaide Electric Supply Company, which was nationalised by the Playford government in 1946, becoming the Electricity Trust of South Australia (ETSA).
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The electricity retail market was opened to competition in 2003 and although competition was expected to result in lower retail costs, prices increased by 23.7% in the market's first year.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] In 2004, the privatisation was deemed to be a failure with consumers paying 60% more for their power and with the state government estimated to lose $3 billion in power generation net income in the first ten years of privatisation.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] In 2012, the industry came under scrutiny for allegedly reducing supply by shutting down generators during periods of peak demand to force prices up.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Increased media attention also revealed that in 2009 the state government had approved a 46% increase in retail prices to cover expected increases in the costs of generation while generation costs had in fact fallen 35% by 2012.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] South Australia has the highest retail price for electricity in the country.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Privatisation led to competition from a variety of companies who now separately provide for the generation, transmission, distribution and retail sales of gas and electricity.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Electricity generation comes from a range of technologies and operators.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] ElectraNet operates the high-voltage electricity transmission network.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] SA Power Networks distributes electricity to end users.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The largest electricity and gas retailing companies are also the largest generating companies.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] The largest fossil fuel power stations are the Torrens Island Power Station gas-fired plant operated by AGL Energy and the Pelican Point Power Station operated by Engie.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] South Australia also has wind and solar power and connections to the national grid.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] Gas is supplied from the Moomba Gas Processing Plant in the Cooper Basin via the Moomba Adelaide Pipeline System and the SEAGas pipeline from Victoria.
[src:apartment/adelaide-p02] In 2011, South Australia generated 18% of its electricity from wind power, and had 51% of the installed capacity of wind generators in Australia.
